# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bacteroides-fragilis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] An **abscess** is a collection of pus that has built up within the tissue of the body, usually caused by bacterial infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Signs and symptoms of abscesses include redness, pain, warmth, and swelling.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The swelling may feel fluid-filled when pressed.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The area of redness often extends beyond the swelling.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Carbuncles and boils are types of abscess that often involve hair follicles, with carbuncles being larger.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] A cyst is related to an abscess, but it contains a material other than pus, and a cyst has a clearly defined wall.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Abscesses can also form internally on internal organs and after surgery.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] They are usually caused by a bacterial infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Often many different types of bacteria are involved in a single infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In many areas of the world, the most common bacteria present are *methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Skin abscesses in particular are overwhelmingly caused by *S. aureus*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Rarely, parasites can cause abscesses; this is more common in the developing world.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Diagnosis of a skin abscess is usually made based on what it looks like and is confirmed by cutting it open.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Ultrasound imaging may be useful in cases in which the diagnosis is not clear.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In abscesses around the anus, computer tomography (CT) may be important to look for deeper infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Standard treatment for most skin or soft tissue abscesses is cutting it open and drainage.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] There appears to be some benefit from also using antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] A small amount of evidence supports not packing the cavity that remains with gauze after drainage.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Closing this cavity right after draining it rather than leaving it open may speed healing without increasing the risk of the abscess returning.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Sucking out the pus with a needle is often not sufficient.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Skin abscesses are common and have become more common in recent years.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Risk factors include intravenous drug use, with rates reported as high as 65% among users.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In 2005, 3.2 million people went to American emergency departments for abscesses.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In Australia, around 13,000 people were hospitalized in 2008 with the condition.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Abscesses may occur in any tissue, but most frequently within the skin surface (where they may be superficial pustules known as boils or deep skin abscesses), in the lungs, brain, teeth, kidneys, and tonsils.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Major complications may include spreading of the abscess material to adjacent or remote tissues, and extensive regional tissue death (gangrene).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The main symptoms and signs of a skin abscess are redness, heat, swelling, pain, and loss of function.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] There may also be high temperature (fever) and chills.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] If superficial, abscesses may be fluctuant when palpated; this wave-like motion is caused by movement of the pus inside the abscess.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] An internal abscess is more difficult to identify and depends on the location of the abscess and the type of infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] General signs include pain in the affected area, a high temperature, and generally feeling unwell.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Internal abscesses rarely heal themselves, so prompt medical attention is indicated if such an abscess is suspected.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] An abscess can potentially be fatal depending on where it is located.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Risk factors for abscess formation include intravenous drug use.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Another possible risk factor is a prior history of disc herniation or other spinal abnormality, though this has not been proven.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Abscesses are caused by bacterial infection, parasites, or foreign substances.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Bacterial infection is the most common cause, particularly *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The more invasive methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA) may also be a source of infection, though it is much rarer.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Among spinal subdural abscesses, methicillin-sensitive *S. aureus* is the most common organism involved.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Rarely parasites can cause abscesses, and this is more common in the developing world.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Specific parasites known to do this include dracunculiasis and myiasis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In immunocompromised people, and particularly those with AIDS, *Toxoplasma gondii* is a frequent cause of widespread abscesses throughout the body, including in the brain.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] An abscess may form anywhere that bacteria can get through the skin, including insect bites, lacerations, puncture wounds, scrapes, IV injection sites, and other small surface-level injuries.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The overwhelming majority of skin abscesses are caused by *Staphylococcus aureus* (methicillin-susceptible or methicillin-resistant), with some studies showing over 90% of documented and cultured skin abscesses being caused by this organism.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Anorectal abscesses can be caused by non-specific obstruction and ensuing infection of the glandular crypts inside the anus or rectum.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Other causes include cancer, trauma, or inflammatory bowel diseases.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] An *incisional abscess* develops as a complication secondary to a surgical incision.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] It presents as redness and warmth at the margins of the incision with purulent drainage.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] If the diagnosis is uncertain, the wound should be aspirated with a needle, with aspiration of pus confirming the diagnosis and availing for Gram stain and bacterial culture.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The cause can be from trauma, surgery, an infection, or a pre-existing condition.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] An abscess is a buildup of pus surrounded by normal body tissue.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In most cases, abscesses are caused by an infectious species of bacteria, and they function to wall off the infection from uninfected tissues.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Organisms or foreign materials destroy the local cells, which results in the release of cytokines.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The cytokines trigger an inflammatory response, which draws large numbers of white blood cells to the area and increases the regional blood flow.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The final structure of the abscess is an abscess wall, or capsule, formed by adjacent healthy cells in an attempt to keep the pus from infecting neighboring structures.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] However, such encapsulation tends to prevent immune cells from attacking bacteria in the pus or from reaching the causative organism or foreign object.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] An abscess is a localized collection of pus (purulent inflammatory tissue) caused by suppuration buried in a tissue, an organ, or a confined space, lined by the pyogenic membrane.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Ultrasound imaging can help in a diagnosis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Abscesses may be classified as either *skin abscesses* or *internal abscesses*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Skin abscesses are common; internal abscesses tend to be harder to diagnose and more serious.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Skin abscesses are also called cutaneous or subcutaneous abscesses.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] For those with a history of intravenous drug use, an X-ray is recommended before treatment to verify that no needle fragments are present.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] If there is also a fever present in this population, infectious endocarditis should be considered.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Abscesses should be differentiated from empyemas, which are accumulations of pus in a preexisting, rather than a newly formed, anatomical cavity.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Other conditions that can cause similar symptoms include: cellulitis, a sebaceous cyst, and necrotising fasciitis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Cellulitis typically also has an erythematous reaction, but does not confer any purulent drainage.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The standard treatment for an uncomplicated skin or soft-tissue abscess is the incision and drainage procedure.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] There does not appear to be any benefit from also using antibiotics in most cases.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] A small amount of evidence did not find a benefit from packing the abscess with gauze.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The abscess should be inspected to see if foreign objects are the cause, which may require their removal.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] If foreign objects are not the cause, incising and draining the abscess is standard treatment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In most cases, a localized injection of lidocaine and epinephrine precedes the incision, to suppress pain.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Most people with an uncomplicated skin abscess should not use antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Antibiotics in addition to standard incision and drainage are recommended in persons with severe abscesses, many sites of infection, rapid disease progression, the presence of cellulitis, symptoms indicating bacterial illness throughout the body, or a health condition causing immunosuppression.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] People who are very young or very old may also need antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] If the abscess does not heal only with incision and drainage, or if the abscess is in a place that is difficult to drain, such as the face, hands, or genitals, then antibiotics may be indicated.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In those cases of abscess which do require antibiotic treatment, *Staphylococcus aureus* bacteria are a common cause and an anti-staphylococcus antibiotic such as flucloxacillin or dicloxacillin is used.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The Infectious Diseases Society of America advises that the draining of an abscess is not enough to address community-acquired methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In those cases, traditional antibiotics may be ineffective.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Alternative antibiotics effective against community-acquired MRSA often include clindamycin, doxycycline, minocycline, and trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The American College of Emergency Physicians advises that typical cases of abscess from MRSA get no benefit from having antibiotic treatment in addition to the standard treatment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Culturing the wound is not needed if standard follow-up care can be provided after the incision and drainage.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Performing a wound culture is unnecessary because it rarely gives information that can be used to guide treatment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In North America, after drainage, an abscess cavity is usually packed, often with special iodoform-treated cloth.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] This is done to absorb and neutralize any remaining exudate as well as to promote draining and prevent premature closure.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Prolonged draining is thought to promote healing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The hypothesis is that though the heart's pumping action can deliver immune and regenerative cells to the edge of an injury, an abscess is by definition a void in which no blood vessels are present.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Packing is thought to provide a wicking action that continuously draws beneficial factors and cells from the body into the void that must be healed.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Discharge is then absorbed by cutaneous bandages, and further wicking is promoted by changing these bandages regularly.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] However, evidence from emergency medicine literature reports that packing wounds after draining, especially smaller wounds, causes pain to the person and does not decrease the rate of recurrence, nor bring faster healing, or fewer physician visits.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] More recently, several North American hospitals have opted for less-invasive loop drainage over standard drainage and wound packing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In one study of 143 pediatric outcomes, a failure rate of 1.4% was reported in the loop group versus 10.5% in the packing group (P<.030), while a separate study reported a 5.5% failure rate among the loop group.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Closing an abscess immediately after draining it appears to speed healing without increasing the risk of recurrence.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] This may not apply to anorectal abscesses, as while they may heal faster, there may be a higher rate of recurrence than those left open.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Appendiceal abscesses are complications of appendicitis, where there is an infected mass on the appendix.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] This condition is estimated to occur in 2–10% of appendicitis cases and is usually treated by surgical removal of the appendix (appendicectomy).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Even without treatment, skin abscesses rarely result in death, as they will naturally break through the skin.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Other types of abscesses are more dangerous.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Brain abscesses may be fatal if untreated.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] When treated, the mortality rate decreases to 5–10%, but it is higher if the abscess ruptures.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In 2005, in the United States, 3.2 million people went to the emergency department for an abscess.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] In Australia, around 13,000 people were hospitalized in 2008 for the disease.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The Latin medical aphorism "*ubi pus, ibi evacua*" expresses "where there is pus, there evacuate it" and is classical advice in the culture of Western medicine.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] Needle exchange programmes often administer or provide referrals for abscess treatment to injection drug users as part of a harm reduction public health strategy.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] An abscess is so called "abscess" because there is an *abscessus* (a going away or departure) of portions of the animal tissue from each other to make room for the suppurated matter lodged between them.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/abscess] The word carbuncle is believed to have originated from the Latin: *carbunculus*, originally a small coal; diminutive of *carbon-*, *carbo*: charcoal or ember, but also a carbuncle stone, "precious stones of a red or fiery colour", usually garnets.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The clinically important anaerobes in decreasing frequency are: 1.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Six genera of Gram-negative rods (*Bacteroides, Prevotella, Porphyromonas, Fusobacterium, Bilophila* and *Sutterella* spp.); 2.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Gram-positive cocci (primarily *Peptostreptococcus* spp.); 3.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Gram-positive spore-forming (*Clostridium* spp.) and non-spore-forming bacilli (*Actinomyces, Propionibacterium, Eubacterium, Lactobacillus* and *Bifidobacterium* spp.); and 4.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Gram-negative cocci (mainly *Veillonella* spp.).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The frequency of isolation of anaerobic bacterial strains varies in different infectious sites.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Mixed infections caused by numerous aerobic and anaerobic bacteria are often observed in clinical situations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Anaerobic bacteria are a common cause of infections, some of which can be serious and life-threatening.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Because anaerobes are the predominant components of the normal flora of the skin and mucous membranes, they are a common cause of infections of endogenous origin.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Because of their fastidious nature, anaerobes are hard to culture and isolate and are often not recovered from infected sites.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The administration of delayed or inappropriate therapy against these organisms may lead to failures in eradication of these infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The isolation of anaerobic bacteria requires adequate methods for collection, transportation and cultivation of clinical specimens.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The management of anaerobic infection is often difficult because of the slow growth of anaerobic organisms, which can delay their identification by the frequent polymicrobial nature of these infections and by the increasing resistance of anaerobic bacteria to antimicrobials.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Anaerobes have been found in infections throughout the human body.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The frequency of the host or patient's recovery depends on the employment of proper methods of collection of specimen, their transportation to the microbiology laboratory and cultivation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The recovery of organisms depends on the site of infection and is related to the adjacent mucous membranes' microbial flora.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Anaerobes are able to cause all types of intracranial infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] These often cause subdural empyema, and brain abscess, and rarely cause epidural abscess and meningitis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The origin of brain abscess is generally an adjacent chronic ear, mastoid, or sinus infection oropharynx, teeth or lungs.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Mastoid and ear or infections generally progress to the temporal lobe or cerebellum, while facial sinusitis commonly causes frontal lobe abscess.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Hematogenous spread of the infection into the CNS often occurs after oropharyngeal, dental, or pulmonary infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Infrequently bacteremia originating of another location or endocarditis can also cause intracranial infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Meningitis due to anaerobic bacteria is infrequent and may follow respiratory tract infection or complicate a cerebrospinal fluid shunt.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Neurological shunt infections are often caused by skin bacteria such as *Cutibacterium acnes*, or in instances of ventriculoperitoneal shunts that perforate the gut, by anaerobes of enteric origin (i.e.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] *Bacteroides fragilis*).*Clostridium perfringens* can cause of brain abscesses and meningitis following intracranial surgery or head trauma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The anaerobes often isolated from brain abscesses complicating respiratory and dental infections are anaerobic Gram-negative bacilli (AGNB, including *Prevotella*, *Porphyromonas*, *Bacteroides*), *Fusobacterium* and *Peptostreptococcus* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Microaerophilic and other streptococci are also often isolated.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Some advocate complete drainage of intracranial abscess, while others use repeated aspirations of the abscess.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Repeated aspirations of an abscess are preferable in those with multiple abscesses or when the abscess is located in a predominate brain site.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Administration of antimicrobials in a high-dose for an extended period of time can offer an alternative treatment strategy in this type of patients and may substitute for surgical evacuation of an abscess.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Because of the poor penetration of many antimicrobial agents through the blood–brain barrier, there are few agents available for the treatment of intracranial infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The antimicrobials with good intracranial penetration are metronidazole, chloramphenicol, penicillins, and meropenem.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Optimally, the selection of antimicrobial is done according to the recovered isolates and their antimicrobial susceptibilities.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] A substantial improvement in patients' survival rate has occurred after the introduction of computed tomography (CT) and other scans and utilization of metronidazole therapy.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Anaerobes can be isolated from most types of upper respiratory tract and head and neck infection, and are especially common in chronic ones.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The predominant organisms are of oropharyngeal flora origin and include AGNB, *Fusobacterium* and *Peptostreptococcus* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Anaerobes involve almost all dental infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] These include dental abscesses, endodontal pulpitis and periodontal (gingivitis and periodontitis) infections, and perimandibular space infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Pulpitis can lead to abscess formation and eventually spread to the mandible and other neck spaces.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] In addition to strict anaerobic bacteria, microaerophilic streptococci and *Streptococcus salivarius* can also be present.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Deep neck infections that develop as a consequence of oral, dental and pharyngeal infections are generally polymicrobial in nature.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] These include extension of retropharyngeal cellulitis or abscess, mediastinitis following esophagus perforation, and dental or periodontal abscess.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] In adults the most common source of aspiration pneumonia is aspiration of oropharyngeal secretions or gastric contents.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] In children the most common cause is aspiration of infected amniotic fluid, or vaginal secretions.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Severe periodontal or gingival diseases are important risk factors for establishment of an anaerobic pleuropulmonary infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Progression of the infection from pneumonitis into necrotizing pneumonia and pulmonary abscess can occur, with or without the development of empyema.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The infection is often polymicrobial in nature and isolates of community-acquired infection (in 60–80% of cases) are aerobic and anaerobic belonging to the individual's oropharyngeal flora.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The anaerobic bacteria commonly recovered are *Prevotella, Porphyromonas, Fusobacterium* and *Peptostreptococcus* spp., and the aerobic bacteria are beta-hemolytic and microaerophilic streptococci.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] It is important that specimens are obtained in a method that avoids their contamination by the oral microflora.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Perforated appendicitis, diverticulitis, inflammatory bowel disease with perforation and gastrointestinal surgery are often associated with polymicrobial infections caused by aerobic and anaerobic bacteria, where the number of isolates can average 12 (two-thirds are generally anaerobes).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The most common aerobic and facultative bacteria are *Escherichia coli*, *Streptococcus* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] (including *Enterococcus* spp.), and the most frequently isolated anaerobic bacteria are the *B. fragilis* group, *Peptostreptococcus* spp., and *Clostridium* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Abdominal infections are characteristically biphasic: an initial stages of generalized peritonitis associated with *Escherichia coli* sepsis, and a later stages, in which intra abdominal abscesses harboring anaerobic bacteria (including *B. fragilis* group) emerge.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The clinical manifestations of secondary peritonitis are a reflection of the underlying disease process.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Fever, diffuse abdominal pain, nausea and vomiting are common.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Physical examination generally show signs of peritoneal inflammation, isuch as rebound tenderness, abdominal wall rigidity and decrease in bowel sounds.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] These early findings may be followed by signs and symptoms of shock.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Biliary tract infection is usually caused by *E. coli, Klebsiella* and *Enterococcus* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Anaerobes (mostly *B. fragilis* group, and rarely *C. perfringens*) can be recovered in complicated infections associated with carcinoma, recurrent infection, obstruction, bile tract surgery or manipulation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Laboratory studies show elevated blood leukocyte count and predominance of polymorphonuclear forms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Radiographs studies may show free air in the peritoneal cavity, evidence of ileus or obstruction and obliteration of the psoas shadow.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Diagnostic ultrasound, gallium and CT scanning may detect appendiceal or other intra-abdominal abscesses.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Polymicrobial postoperative wound infections can occur.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Treatment of mixed aerobic and anaerobic abdominal infections requires the utilization of antimicrobials effective against both components of the infection as well as surgical correction and drainage of pus.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Single and easily accessible abscesses can be drained percutaneously.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Getting adequate microbiological cultures is essential.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] It is important to avoid contaminating the culture with the normal genital flora.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Methods that can ensure adequate cultures are laparoscopy, culdocentesis, or obtaining quantitative endometrial cultures employing a telescoping catheter.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The anaerobes often recovered include *Prevotella bivia, Prevotella disiens*, and *Peptostreptococcus, Porphyromonas* and *Clostridium* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] *Bacteroides fragilis* group is rarely recovered in these infections compared to intra-abdominal infection.*Actinomyces* spp. and *Eubacterium nodatum* are often recovered in infections associated with intrauterine devices.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] *Mobiluncus* spp. can be associated with bacterial vaginosis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The aerobic bacteria also found mixed with these anaerobic bacteria include Enterobacteriaceae, *Streptococcus* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] (including groups A and B), *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, *Chlamydia* spp. and *Mycoplasma hominis*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Free gas in the tissues, abscess formation and foul-smelling discharge is commonly associated with the presence of anaerobic bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Treatment of these infections includes the use of antimicrobials active against all of the potential aerobic and anaerobic bacterial pathogens.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Antimicrobials against sexually transmissible pathogens should also be administered.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The infections that frequently involve anaerobic bacteria include superficial infections, including infected paronychia, infected human or animal bites, cutaneous ulcers, cellulitis, pyoderma, and hidradenitis suppurativa.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Secondary infected sites include secondary infected diaper rash, gastrostomy or tracheostomy site wounds, scabies or kerion infections, eczema, psoriasis, poison ivy, atopic dermatitis, eczema herpeticum, infected subcutaneous sebaceous or inclusion cysts, and postsurgical wound infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Deeper anaerobic soft-tissue infections are necrotizing fasciitis, necrotizing synergistic cellulitis, gas gangrene and crepitus cellulitis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] These can involve the fascia as well as the muscle surrounded by the fascia, and may also induce myositis and myonecrosis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The isolates found in soft-tissue infections can vary depending on the type of infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The infection's location and the circumstances causing the infection can also influence the nature of the microorganisms recovered.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Bacteria that are members of the 'normal flora' of the region of the infection are often also isolated from lesions involving anaerobic bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Specimens obtained from wounds and subcutaneous tissue infections and abscesses in the rectal area (perirectal abscess, decubitus ulcer) or that are of gut flora origin(i.e. diabetic foot infection) often to yield colonic flora organisms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] These are generally *B. fragilis* group, *Clostridium* spp., Enterobacteriaceae and *Enterococcus* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] On the other hand, infections in and around the oropharynx, or infections that originate from that location, frequently contain oral flora organisms (i.e. paronychia, bites, breast abscess).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] These bacteria include pigmented *Prevotella* and *Porphyromonas, Fusobacterium* and *Peptostreptococcus* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Skin flora organisms such as *S. aureus* and *Streptococcus* spp., or nosocomially acquired microorganisms can be recovered at all body locations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Human bite infections often contain *Eikenella* spp. and animal bites harbor *Pasteurella multocida* in addition to oral flora.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Anaerobes infections are often polymicrobial in nature, and sometimes (i.e. decubitus ulcers, diabetic foot ulcer) they are complicated by bacteremia and/or osteomyelitis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Infections which are in the deep tissues (necrotizing cellulitis, fasciitis and myositis) often include *Clostridium* spp., *S. pyogenes* or polymicrobic combinations of both aerobic and anaerobic bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Gas in the tissues and putrid-like pus with a gray thin quality are often found in these infections, and they are frequently associated with a bacteremia and high mortality rate.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Treatment of deep-seated soft-tissue infections includes: vigorous surgical management that includes surgical debridement and drainage.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Even though there are no controlled studies that support this approach improvement of the involved tissues oxygenation by enhancement of blood supply and administration of hyperbaric oxygen, especially in clostridial infection, may be helpful.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Anaerobic bacteria are often found in osteomyelitis of the long bones especially after trauma and fracture, osteomyelitis associated with peripheral vascular disease, and decubitus ulcers and osteomyelitis of the facial and cranial bones.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Many of these bone infections are polymicrobial in nature.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Cranial and facial bones anaerobic osteomyelitis often originates by the spread of the infection from a contiguous soft-tissue source or from dental, sinus, or ear infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The high concentration of anaerobic bacteria in the oral cavity explains their importance in cranial and facial bone infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The high number of gut anaerobes in pelvic osteomyelitis is generally caused by their spread from decubitus ulcers sites.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The anaerobic organisms in osteomyelitis associated with peripheral vascular disease generally reach the bone from adjacent soft-tissue ulcers.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Long bones osteomyelitis is often caused by trauma, hematogenic spread, or the presence of a prosthetic device.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Septic arthritis due to anaerobic bacteria is frequently associated with contiguous or hematogenous infection spread, prosthetic joints and trauma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Most septic arthritis cases caused by anaerobic bacteria are monomicrobial.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The predominant anaerobic bacteria isolated are *Peptostreptococcus* spp. and *Propionibacterium acnes* (frequently found in prosthetic joint infection),*B. fragilis* and *Fusobacterium* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] (frequently found in infections of hematogenic origin), and *Clostridium* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] (frequently found in infections after trauma).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The incidence of anaerobic bacteria in bacteremia varies between 5% and 15%, The incidence of anaerobic bacteremia in the 1990s declined to about 4% (0.5–12%) of all cases of bacteremias.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] A resurgence in bacteremia due to anaerobic bacteria was observed recently.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] This is explained by a greater number of anaerobic bacteremia in patients with complex underlying disease or those that are immunosuppressed.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The commonest isolates are B. fragilis group (over 75% of anaerobic isolates), *Clostridium* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The type of bacteria involved in bacteremia is greatly influenced by the infection's portal of entry and the underlying disease.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The association of these organisms is related to the origin of the initial infection and the endogenous bacterial flora at that site.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The clinical presentations of anaerobic bacteremia are not different from those observed in aerobic bacteremia, except for the infection's signs observed at the portal of entry of the infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] It often includes fever, chills, hypotension, shock, leukocytosis, anemia and disseminated intravascular coagulation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Clinical features that are characteristic of anaerobicbacteremia include hyperbilirubinemia, metastatic lesions, and suppurative thrombophlebitis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The mortality rate varies between 15% and 30% and can be improved in those who are diagnosed early and receive appropriate antimicrobial therapy and their primary infection when present is resolved.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The newborn's exposure to the maternal vaginal bacterial flora which contains aerobic and anaerobic bacterial flora can lead to the development of anaerobic bacterial infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] These infections include cellulitis of the site of fetal monitoring (caused by *Bacteroides* spp.), bacteremia, aspiration pneumonia (caused by *Bacteroides* spp.), conjunctivitis (caused by clostridia), omphalitis (caused by mixed flora), and infant botulism.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Clostridial species may play a role in necrotizing enterocolitis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Management of these infection necessitates treating of the underlying condition(s) when present, and administration of proper antimicrobial therapy.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Condition predisposing to anaerobic infections include: exposure of a sterile body location to a high inoculum of indigenous bacteria of mucous membrane flora origin, inadequate blood supply and tissue necrosis which lower the oxidation and reduction potential which support the growth of anaerobes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Conditions which can lower the blood supply and can predispose to anaerobic infection are: trauma, foreign body, malignancy, surgery, edema, shock, colitis and vascular disease.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Other predisposing conditions include splenectomy, neutropenia, immunosuppression, hypogammaglobinemia, leukemia, collagen vascular disease and cytotoxic drugs and diabetes mellitus.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] A preexisting infection caused by aerobic or facultative organisms can alter the local tissue conditions and make them more favorable for the growth of anaerobes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Impairment in defense mechanisms due to anaerobic conditions can also favor anaerobic infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The hallmarks of anaerobic infection include suppuration, establishment of an abscess, thrombophlebitis and gangrenous destruction of tissue with gas generation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Anaerobic bacteria are very commonly recovered in chronic infections, and are often found following the failure of therapy with antimicrobials that are ineffective against them, such as trimethoprim–sulfamethoxazole (co-trimoxazole), aminoglycosides, and the earlier quinolones.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Some infections are more likely to be caused by anaerobic bacteria, and they should be suspected in most instances.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Some solid malignant tumors, (colonic, uterine and bronchogenic, and head and neck necrotic tumors, are more likely to become secondarily infected with anaerobes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The lack of oxygen within the tumor that are proximal to the endogenous adjacent mucosal flora can predispose such infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Recovery from an anaerobic infection depends on adequate and rapid management.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The main principles of managing anaerobic infections are neutralizing the toxins produced by anaerobic bacteria, preventing the local proliferation of these organisms by altering the environment and preventing their dissemination and spread to healthy tissues.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Toxin can be neutralized by specific antitoxins, mainly in infections caused by Clostridia (tetanus and botulism).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Controlling the environment can be attained by draining the pus, surgical debriding of necrotic tissue, improving blood circulation, alleviating any obstruction and by improving tissue oxygenation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Therapy with hyperbaric oxygen (HBO) may also be useful.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The main goal of antimicrobials is in restricting the local and systemic spread of the microorganisms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] An antimicrobial effective against Gram-negative enteric bacilli (i.e. aminoglycoside) or an anti-pseudomonal cephalosporin (i.e. cefepime) are generally added to metronidazole, and occasionally cefoxitin when treating intra-abdominal infections to provide coverage for these organisms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Clindamycin should not be used as a single agent as empiric therapy for abdominal infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Penicillin can be added to metronidazole in treating of intracranial, pulmonary and dental infections to provide coverage against microaerophilic streptococci, and Actinomyces.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Oral agents adequate for polymicrobial oral infections include the combinations of amoxicillin plus clavulanate, clindamycin and metronidazole plus a macrolide.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Penicillin can be added to metronidazole in the treating dental and intracranial infections to cover *Actinomyces* spp., microaerophilic streptococci, and *Arachnia* spp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] A macrolide can be added to metronidazole in treating upper respiratory infections to cover *S. aureus* and aerobic streptococci.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Penicillin can be added to clindamycin to supplement its coverage against *Peptostreptococcus* spp. and other Gram-positive anaerobic organisms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Doxycycline is added to most regimens in the treatment of pelvic infections to cover chlamydia and mycoplasma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Penicillin is effective for bacteremia caused by non-beta lactamase producing bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] However, other agents should be used for the therapy of bacteremia caused by beta-lactamase producing bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] Because the length of therapy for anaerobic infections is generally longer than for infections due to aerobic and facultative anaerobic bacteria, oral therapy is often substituted for parenteral treatment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/anaerobic-infection] The agents available for oral therapy are limited and include amoxicillin plus clavulanate, clindamycin, chloramphenicol and metronidazole.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotic resistance is a serious result of AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Resistance arises through spontaneous mutation, horizontal gene transfer, and increased selective pressure from antibiotic overuse, both in medicine and agriculture, which accelerates resistance development.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Preventive measures, such as using narrow-spectrum antibiotics and improving hygiene practices, aim to reduce the spread of resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) claims that AMR is one of the top global public health and development threats, estimating that bacterial AMR was directly responsible for 1.27 million global deaths in 2019 and contributed to 4.95 million deaths.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The burden of AMR is immense, with nearly 5 million annual deaths associated with resistant infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Infections from AMR microbes are more challenging to treat and often require costly alternative therapies that may have more severe side effects.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Moreover, the WHO and other international bodies warn that AMR could lead to up to 10 million deaths annually by 2050 unless actions are taken.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Global initiatives, such as calls for international AMR treaties, emphasize coordinated efforts to limit misuse, fund research, and provide access to necessary antimicrobials in developing nations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, the COVID-19 pandemic redirected resources and scientific attention away from AMR, intensifying the challenge.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance means that a microorganism is resistant to an antimicrobial drug that was once able to treat an infection by that microorganism.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Resistance is a property of the microbe, not a person or other organism infected by a microbe.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] All types of microbes can develop drug resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Thus, there are antibiotic, antifungal, antiviral and antiparasitic resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotic resistance is a subset of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This more specific resistance is linked to bacteria and thus broken down into two further subsets, microbiological and clinical.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Microbiological resistance is the most common and occurs from genes, mutated or inherited, that allow the bacteria to resist the mechanism to kill the microbe associated with certain antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Clinical resistance is shown through the failure of many therapeutic techniques where the bacteria that are normally susceptible to a treatment become resistant after surviving the outcome of the treatment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In both cases of acquired resistance, the bacteria can pass the genetic catalyst for resistance through horizontal gene transfer: conjugation, transduction, or transformation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This allows the resistance to spread across the same species of pathogen or even similar bacterial pathogens.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] WHO report released April 2014 stated, "this serious threat is no longer a prediction for the future, it is happening right now in every region of the world and has the potential to affect anyone, of any age, in any country.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2024, nearly 5 million deaths were associated with AMR and deaths attributable to AMR numbered 1.27 million.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] One in five people who died due to AMR were children under five years old.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2018, WHO considered antibiotic resistance to be one of the biggest threats to global health, food security and development.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control calculated that in 2015 there were 671,689 infections in the EU and European Economic Area caused by antibiotic-resistant bacteria, resulting in 33,110 deaths.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Most were acquired in healthcare settings.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2019 there were 133,000 deaths caused by AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] AMR is driven largely by the misuse and overuse of antimicrobials.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] They reproduce and spread quickly, and they also can adapt to their environment and change how well they can survive.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Yet, at the same time, many people do not have access to essential antimicrobials.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This leads to microbes either evolving a defense against drugs used to treat them, or certain strains of microbes that have a natural resistance to antimicrobials becoming much more prevalent than the ones that are easily defeated with medication.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Genetic changes can also occur, which would allow the microbe to survive.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] While antimicrobial resistance does occur naturally over time, the use of antimicrobial agents in a variety of settings both within the healthcare industry and outside of has led to antimicrobial resistance becoming increasingly more prevalent.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Although many microbes develop resistance to antibiotics over time through natural mutation, overprescribing and inappropriate prescription of antibiotics have accelerated the problem.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] During mutation, when replication happens, these mutations help individual microbes survive exposure.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] (NIAID, 2025) It is possible that as many as 1 in 3 prescriptions written for antibiotics are unnecessary.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Every year, approximately 154 million prescriptions for antibiotics are written.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Of these, up to 46 million are unnecessary or inappropriate for the condition that the patient has.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Microbes may naturally develop resistance through genetic mutations that occur during cell division, and although random mutations are rare, many microbes reproduce frequently and rapidly, increasing the chances of members of the population acquiring a mutation that increases resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In contrast to that, recent research suggests that, contrary to the traditional model of rapid genetic mutation, mycobacteria maintain high genomic stability under antibiotic pressure, relying instead on phenotypic tolerance and DNA-repair mechanisms for survival.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Many individuals stop taking antibiotics when they begin to feel better.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] When this occurs, it is possible that the microbes that are less susceptible to treatment still remain in the body.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] If these microbes are able to continue to reproduce, this can lead to an infection by bacteria that are less susceptible or even resistant to an antibiotic.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Microbes may also get genes from each other, which makes them drug-resistant.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Bacteria that have drug-resistant DNA often transfer a copy of these genes to the other bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This process, known as horizontal gene transfer, allows resistance genes to spread rapidly between different bacterial species through mechanisms such as conjugation, transformation, and transduction.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Bacteria become resistant to antibiotics by changing themselves or acquiring resistance genes from other bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Over the past 20 years, antimicrobial resistance (AMR) has grown, making common infections like respiratory infections, urinary tract infections, STDs, and tuberculosis harder to treat.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] New antibiotics are not being developed fast enough and may lead to a "post-antibiotic era" where some infections are untreatable.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] AMR makes infections more difficult and costly to treat.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Proper antibiotic use—correct drug, dose, and duration—and strict hospital hygiene are essential.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Combating AMR requires cooperation among governments, healthcare workers, researchers, pharmaceutical companies, farmers, and the public through responsible antibiotic use, monitoring resistance, limiting antibiotics in animals, and improving access to medicines, vaccines, and tests.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Prevention is the most effective strategy.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Along with careful antibiotic use, there is a need for new drugs, alternative treatments, better diagnostics, and vaccines.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Without coordinated global action, vital medical procedures like surgery, organ transplants, neonatal care, and cancer treatment could be at risk.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance can evolve naturally due to continued exposure to antimicrobials.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Natural selection means that organisms that are able to adapt to their environment, survive, and continue to produce offspring.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] As a result, the types of microorganisms that are able to survive over time with continued attack by certain antimicrobial agents will naturally become more prevalent in the environment, and those without this resistance will become obsolete.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Some contemporary antimicrobial resistances have also evolved naturally before the use of antimicrobials of human clinical uses.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] For instance, methicillin-resistance evolved as a pathogen of hedgehogs, possibly as a co-evolutionary adaptation of the pathogen to hedgehogs that are infected by a dermatophyte that naturally produces antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Also, many soil fungi and bacteria are natural competitors and the original antibiotic penicillin discovered by Alexander Fleming rapidly lost clinical effectiveness in treating humans and, furthermore, none of the other natural penicillins (F, K, N, X, O, U1 or U6) are currently in clinical use.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance can be acquired from other microbes through swapping genes in a process termed horizontal gene transfer.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This means that once a gene for resistance to an antibiotic appears in a microbial community, it can then spread to other microbes, potentially moving from a non-disease causing microbe to a disease-causing microbe.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This process is heavily driven by the natural selection processes that happen during antibiotic use or misuse.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Over time, most of the strains of bacteria and infections present will be the type resistant to the antimicrobial agent being used to treat them, making this agent now ineffective to defeat most microbes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] With the increased use of antimicrobial agents, there is a speeding up of this natural process.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In the vast majority of countries, antibiotics can only be prescribed by a doctor and supplied by a pharmacy.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Self-medication by consumers is defined as "the taking of medicines on one's own initiative or on another person's suggestion, who is not a certified medical professional", and it has been identified as one of the primary reasons for the evolution of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Self-medication with antibiotics is an unsuitable way of using them but a common practice in resource-constrained countries.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The practice exposes individuals to the risk of bacteria that have developed antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Many people resort to this out of necessity, when access to a physician is unavailable, or when patients have a limited amount of time or money to see a doctor.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This increased access makes it extremely easy to obtain antimicrobials.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] An example is India, where in the state of Punjab 73% of the population resorted to treating their minor health issues and chronic illnesses through self-medication.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Self-medication is higher outside the hospital environment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The prevalence of self-medication in low- and middle-income countries (LMICs) ranges from 8.1% to 93%.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Accessibility, affordability, and conditions of health facilities, as well as the health-seeking behavior, are factors that influence self-medication in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] To determine the public's knowledge and preconceived notions on antibiotic resistance, a screening of 3,537 articles published in Europe, Asia, and North America was done.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Of the 55,225 total people surveyed in the articles, 70% had heard of antibiotic resistance previously, but 88% of those people thought it referred to some type of physical change in the human body.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Clinical misuse by healthcare professionals is another contributor to increased antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Studies done in the US show that the indication for treatment of antibiotics, choice of the agent used, and the duration of therapy was incorrect in up to 50% of the cases studied.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In 2010 and 2011 about a third of antibiotic prescriptions in outpatient settings in the United States were not necessary.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Another study in an intensive care unit in a major hospital in France has shown that 30% to 60% of prescribed antibiotics were unnecessary.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These inappropriate uses of antimicrobial agents promote the evolution of antimicrobial resistance by supporting the bacteria in developing genetic alterations that lead to resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This demonstrates that many doctors underestimate the impact that their own prescribing habits have on antimicrobial resistance as a whole.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] It also confirms that some physicians may be overly cautious and prescribe antibiotics for both medical or legal reasons, even when clinical indications for use of these medications are not always confirmed.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This can lead to unnecessary antimicrobial use, a pattern which may have worsened during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Studies have shown that common misconceptions about the effectiveness and necessity of antibiotics to treat common mild illnesses contribute to their overuse.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Important to the conversation of antibiotic use is the veterinary medical system.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Veterinary oversight is required by law for all medically important antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Veterinarians use the Pharmacokinetic/pharmacodynamic model (PK/PD) approach to ensuring that the correct dose of the drug is delivered to the correct place at the correct timing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Increased antibiotic use during the early waves of the COVID-19 pandemic may exacerbate this global health challenge.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Moreover, pandemic burdens on some healthcare systems may contribute to antibiotic-resistant infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The use of disinfectants such as alcohol-based hand sanitizers, and antiseptic hand wash may also have the potential to increase antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Overuse of disinfectants can lead to mutations that induce antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] On the other hand, "increased hand hygiene, decreased international travel, and decreased elective hospital procedures may have reduced AMR pathogen selection and spread in the short term" during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Critically ill patients are prone to infections, and because of that, they often require antimicrobials.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The more antimicrobials, the more resistance one becomes to it.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) significantly strains healthcare systems and national economies.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The World Bank estimates that by 2050, AMR could increase healthcare costs by around US$1 trillion and cause global economic losses of US$1–3.4 trillion annually by 2030.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Resistant infections are harder to treat, often requiring longer hospital stays, additional tests, and stronger, more expensive medications, placing extra pressure on hospitals and health systems, especially during pandemics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] A 2024 United Nations High-Level Meeting on AMR has pledged to reduce deaths associated with bacterial AMR by 10% over the next six years.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In their first major declaration on the issue since 2016, global leaders also committed to raising $100 million to update and implement AMR action plans.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, the final draft of the declaration omitted an earlier target to reduce antibiotic use in animals by 30% by 2030, due to opposition from meat-producing countries and the farming industry.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Critics argue this omission is a major weakness, as livestock accounts for around 73% of global sales of antimicrobial agents, including antibiotics, antivirals, and antiparasitics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Considering the complex interactions between humans, animals and the environment, it is also important to consider the environmental aspects and contributors to antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] One of these factors is human and hospital waste, which is a substantial contributor to environmental antimicrobial resistance (AMR).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] It is estimated that around 50–80% of antibiotics are passed unmetabolized in urine and 4–30% in feces, causing large quantities of active antibiotics to enter sewage systems.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Sewage environments contain high levels of antimicrobial-resistant bacteria (ARB), antimicrobial resistance genes (ARGs), and mobile genetic elements such as plasmids, which enable rapid gene exchange.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wastewater treatment plants (WWTPs) are typically not designed to remove AMR; in some cases, multidrug-resistant species such as *Escherichia, Shigella, and Klebsiella* can increase twofold in treated wastewater.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA) has also been detected in both raw and treated sewage.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Agriculture is also a major contributor to environmental AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Manure from livestock (such as cattle, sheep, etc.) contains residual antibiotics, which enter the soil as farmers usually use it as fertilizer.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These are typically at levels of 1–10 mg/kg, and also contain ARBs and ARGs.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] One megaton of antibiotics has been estimated to have entered global soils through manure application.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Pathogens can survive in soil for up to 10 years and on plant surfaces for up to 1 year, thereby enabling long-term environmental continuation of AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Because manure can be applied to diverse crops, residual antibiotics and resistance genes can enter plant tissues and the surrounding soil microbiota, contributing to AMR detected on fruits and vegetables.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Heavy metals in soil, often introduced through fertilizers or industrial processes, can drive cross- and co-resistance mechanisms that select for antibiotic-resistant bacteria even when no antibiotics are present.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Similar selective results happen with biocides and pesticides.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Aquaculture is an underrecognized source of environmental AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Approximately 70% of antibiotics administered in aquaculture enter surrounding waterways, and tetracycline-resistant genes have been found even in isolated environments such as Antarctica and the Arctic.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotic usage varies substantially across countries, showing the major differences in regulatory oversight.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] High antibiotic use in many Asian aquaculture systems has added to the elevated levels of clinically important resistance genes in sediments and river systems.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Recent research has shown that AMR also occurs through the air.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Airborne resistance genes have been detected at high levels in major urban centers, and farms have been determined as hotspots for airborne AMR, with resistance markers detected in the air surrounding animal operations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The antimicrobial resistance crisis also extends to the food industry, specifically with food producing animals.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] With an ever-increasing human population, there is constant pressure to intensify productivity in many agricultural sectors, including the production of meat as a source of protein.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotics are fed to livestock to act as growth supplements, and a preventive measure to decrease the likelihood of infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Farmers typically use antibiotics in animal feed to improve growth rates and prevent infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, this is illogical as antibiotics are used to treat infections and not prevent infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] 80% of antibiotic use in the U.S. is for agricultural purposes and about 70% of these are medically important.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Overusing antibiotics gives the bacteria time to adapt leaving higher doses or even stronger antibiotics needed to combat the infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Though antibiotics for growth promotion were banned throughout the EU in 2006, 40 countries still use antibiotics to promote growth.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This can result in the transfer of resistant bacterial strains into the food that humans eat, causing potentially fatal transfer of disease.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] While the practice of using antibiotics as growth promoters does result in better yields and meat products, it is a major issue and needs to be decreased to prevent antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Though the evidence linking antimicrobial usage in livestock to antimicrobial resistance is limited, the World Health Organization Advisory Group on Integrated Surveillance of Antimicrobial Resistance strongly recommended the reduction of use of medically important antimicrobials in livestock.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Additionally, the Advisory Group stated that such antimicrobials should be expressly prohibited for both growth promotion and disease prevention in food producing animals.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] By mapping antimicrobial consumption in livestock, it was predicted that in 228 countries there would be a total 67% increase in consumption of antibiotics by livestock by 2030.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In some countries such as Brazil, Russia, India, China, and South Africa it is predicted that a 99% increase will occur.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Several countries have restricted the use of antibiotics in livestock, including Canada, China, Japan, and the US.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These restrictions are sometimes associated with a reduction of the prevalence of antimicrobial resistance in humans.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Most pesticides protect crops against insects and plants, but in some cases antimicrobial pesticides are used to protect against various microorganisms such as bacteria, viruses, fungi, algae, and protozoa.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The overuse of many pesticides in an effort to have a higher yield of crops has resulted in many of these microbes evolving a tolerance against these antimicrobial agents.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Currently there are over 4000 antimicrobial pesticides registered with the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and sold to market, showing the widespread use of these agents.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] It is estimated that for every single meal a person consumes, 0.3 g of pesticides is used, as 90% of all pesticide use is in agriculture.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] A majority of these products are used to help defend against the spread of infectious diseases, and hopefully protect public health.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] But out of the large amount of pesticides used, it is also estimated that less than 0.1% of those antimicrobial agents, actually reach their targets.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] That leaves over 99% of all pesticides used available to contaminate other resources.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In soil, air, and water these antimicrobial agents are able to spread, coming in contact with more microorganisms and leading to these microbes evolving mechanisms to tolerate and further resist pesticides.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The use of antifungal azole pesticides that drive environmental azole resistance have been linked to azole resistance cases in the clinical setting.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The same issues confront the novel antifungal classes (e.g. orotomides) which are again being used in both the clinic and agriculture.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wildlife, including wild and migratory birds, serve as indicators of ecosystem health.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] They act as a reservoir for zoonotic diseases and antimicrobial-resistant organisms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Birds are a key link between the transmission of zoonotic diseases to human populations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] By the same token, increased contact between wild birds and human populations (including domesticated animals), has increased the amount of anti-microbial resistance (AMR) to the bird population.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The introduction of AMR to wild birds positively correlates with human pollution and increased human contact.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Additionally, wild birds can participate in horizontal gene transfer with bacteria, leading to the transmission of antibiotic-resistant genes (ARG).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] For simplicity, wild bird populations can be divided into two major categories, wild sedentary birds and wild migrating birds.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wild sedentary bird exposure to AMR is through increased contact with densely populated areas, human waste, domestic animals, and domestic animal/livestock waste.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Especially if they are predators, wild, sedentary birds can come into contact with prey that interact more closely with humans.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Wild migrating birds interact with sedentary birds in different environments along their migration route.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This increases the rate and diversity of AMR across varying ecosystems.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Neglect of wildlife in the global discussions surrounding health security and AMR, creates large barriers to true AMR surveillance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The surveillance of antimicrobial-resistant resistant organisms in wild birds is a potential metric for the rate of AMR in the environment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] This surveillance also allows for further investigation into the transmission routes between different ecosystems and human populations (including domesticated animals and livestock).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Such information gathered from wild bird biomes, can help identify patterns of diseased transmission and better target interventions.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These targeted interventions can inform the use of antimicrobial agents and reduce the persistence of multidrug resistant organisms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Recent studies demonstrate the importance of wild birds as sentinels for AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] For example, *Escherichia coli* isolated from free-ranging Bonelli's eagles (*Aquila fasciata*) in eastern Spain showed that 53.3% of isolates were resistant to at least one antimicrobial, and 29.3% were multidrug-resistant, despite the species' minimal exposure to human-associated environments.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The study also reported resistance to colistin and meropenem, two last-resort antibiotics, and documented 19 different multidrug-resistance patterns, suggesting persistent and heterogeneous selective pressures in the environment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Because Bonelli's eagles live far from humans and urban areas, they acquire resistance largely through interactions with prey species that interact with humans.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] These findings demonstrate how AMR can spread into remote ecosystems via indirect pathways, strengthening the role of wild birds, particularly apex predators, as effective bioindicators in AMR surveillance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Permafrost is a term used to refer to any ground that remained frozen for two years or more, with the oldest known examples continuously frozen for around 700,000 years.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] In the recent decades, permafrost has been rapidly thawing due to climate change.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] The cold preserves any organic matter inside the permafrost, and it is possible for microorganisms to resume their life functions once it thaws.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] While some common pathogens such as influenza, smallpox or the bacteria associated with pneumonia have failed to survive intentional attempts to revive them, more cold-adapted microorganisms such as anthrax, or several ancient plant and amoeba viruses, have successfully survived prolonged thaw.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Some scientists have argued that the inability of known causative agents of contagious diseases to survive being frozen and thawed makes this threat unlikely.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Instead, there have been suggestions that when modern pathogenic bacteria interact with the ancient ones, they may, through horizontal gene transfer, pick up genetic sequences which are associated with antimicrobial resistance, exacerbating an already difficult issue.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Antibiotics to which permafrost bacteria have displayed at least some resistance include chloramphenicol, streptomycin, kanamycin, gentamicin, tetracycline, spectinomycin and neomycin.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] However, other studies show that resistance levels in ancient bacteria to modern antibiotics remain lower than in the contemporary bacteria from the active layer of thawed ground above them, which may mean that this risk is "no greater" than from any other soil.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] There have been increasing public calls for global collective action to address the threat, including a proposal for an international treaty on antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] Further detail and attention is still needed to recognize and measure trends in resistance on the international level; the idea of a global tracking system has been suggested but implementation has yet to occur.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p01] A system of this nature would provide insight to areas of high resistance as well as information necessary for evaluating programs, introducing interventions and other changes made to fight or reverse antibiotic resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) is commonly described within a *One Health* framework, which emphasizes the interconnected relationships between human health, animal health, and the environment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial use in clinical medicine, veterinary practice, and agriculture has been associated with the selection and spread of resistant microorganisms across these sectors.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Research indicates that resistant bacteria and antimicrobial resistance genes can move between humans, animals, and environmental reservoirs through multiple pathways, including food production systems, direct contact, and exposure to contaminated water or soil.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These pathways contribute to the persistence and wider dissemination of antimicrobial resistance beyond individual settings.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Environmental sources have been increasingly examined in relation to AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Wastewater systems, agricultural runoff, and pharmaceutical residues have been identified as potential reservoirs where resistant microorganisms and resistance genes may persist.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Such reservoirs may facilitate ongoing transmission between environmental, animal, and human populations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Efforts to address AMR within a One Health framework typically involve coordinated strategies across sectors, including antimicrobial stewardship, infection prevention and control, and improvements in sanitation and hygiene.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Evidence from systematic reviews suggests that interventions such as farm biosecurity and water, sanitation, and hygiene (WASH) practices may reduce antimicrobial use and contribute to limiting the development and spread of resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Delaying or minimizing the use of antibiotics for certain conditions may help safely reduce their use.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial treatment duration should be based on the infection and other health problems a person may have.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For many infections once a person has improved there is little evidence that stopping treatment causes more resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some, therefore, feel that stopping early may be reasonable in some cases.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Other infections, however, do require long courses regardless of whether a person feels better.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Delaying antibiotics for ailments such as a sore throat and otitis media may have no difference in the rate of complications compared with immediate antibiotics, for example.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] When treating respiratory tract infections, clinical judgement is required as to the appropriate treatment (delayed or immediate antibiotic use).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] ResistanceOpen is an online global map of antimicrobial resistance developed by HealthMap which displays aggregated data on antimicrobial resistance from publicly available and user submitted data.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The website can display data for a 25 miles (40 km) radius from a location.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Users may submit data from antibiograms for individual hospitals or laboratories.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] European data is from the EARS-Net (European Antimicrobial Resistance Surveillance Network), part of the ECDC.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] ResistanceMap is a website by the Center for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy and provides data on antimicrobial resistance on a global level.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO's AMR global action plan also recommends antimicrobial resistance surveillance in animals.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Initial steps in the EU for establishing the veterinary counterpart EARS-Vet (EARS-Net for veterinary medicine) have been made.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] AMR data from pets in particular is scarce, but needed to support antibiotic stewardship in veterinary medicine.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] By comparison there is a lack of national and international monitoring programs for antifungal resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial stewardship programmes appear useful in reducing rates of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The antimicrobial stewardship program will also provide pharmacists with the knowledge to educate patients that antibiotics will not work for a virus for example.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Excessive antimicrobial use has become one of the top contributors to the evolution of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Since the beginning of the antimicrobial era, antimicrobials have been used to treat a wide range of infectious diseases.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Overuse of antimicrobials has become the primary cause of rising levels of antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Prescribers are willing to prescribe antimicrobials to individuals who believe that antimicrobials can cure nearly all illnesses, including viral infections like the common cold.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In an analysis of drug prescriptions, 36% of individuals with a cold or an upper respiratory infection (both usually viral in origin) were given prescriptions for antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These prescriptions increase the risk of further evolution of antibiotic resistant bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Using antimicrobials without prescription is another driving force leading to the overuse of antibiotics to self-treat diseases like the common cold, cough, fever, and dysentery resulting in an epidemic of antibiotic resistance in countries like Bangladesh, risking its spread around the globe.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Introducing strict antibiotic stewardship in the outpatient setting to reduce inappropriate prescribing of antibiotics may reduce the emerging bacterial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO AWaRe (Access, Watch, Reserve) guidance and antibiotic book has been introduced to guide antibiotic choice for the 30 most common infections in adults and children to reduce inappropriate prescribing in primary care and hospitals.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Narrow-spectrum antibiotics are preferred due to their lower resistance potential, and broad-spectrum antibiotics are only recommended for people with more severe symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some antibiotics are more likely to confer resistance, so are kept as reserve antibiotics in the AWaRe book.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Various diagnostic strategies have been employed to prevent the overuse of antifungal therapy in the clinic, proving a safe alternative to empirical antifungal therapy, and thus underpinning antifungal stewardship schemes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial stewardship teams in hospitals are encouraging optimal use of antimicrobials.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The goals of antimicrobial stewardship are to help practitioners pick the right drug at the right dose and duration of therapy while preventing misuse and minimizing the development of resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Stewardship interventions may reduce the length of stay by an average of slightly over 1 day while not increasing the risk of death.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Dispensing the exact number of antibiotic pharmaceutical units necessary to complete an ongoing treatment can reduce excess antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A 2025 cross-sectional study of 125 pharmacists at a UK NHS Foundation Trust examined knowledge, attitudes, and perceptions regarding antimicrobial stewardship following the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The study found that more than 85% of pharmacists recognized antimicrobial resistance as a public health concern.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, the pandemic created challenges, with 80% reporting that COVID-19 patient conditions influenced antibiotic prescription.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A 2026 systematic review of 73 studies examined arthropod-mediated pathogen transmission in hospitals.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Research indicates that cockroaches, flies, and ants frequently harbor multidrug-resistant bacteria, fungi, and viruses.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] While direct causality is difficult to prove, genetic evidence links these pests to hospital-associated infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Given the volume of care provided in primary care (general practice), recent strategies have focused on reducing unnecessary antimicrobial prescribing in this setting.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Simple interventions, such as written information explaining when taking antibiotics is not necessary, for example in common infections of the upper respiratory tract, have been shown to reduce antibiotic prescribing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Various tools are also available to help professionals decide if prescribing antimicrobials is necessary.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Parental expectations, driven by the worry for their children's health, can influence how often children are prescribed antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Parents often rely on their clinician for advice and reassurance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However a lack of plain language information and not having adequate time for consultation negatively impacts this relationship.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In effect parents often rely on past experiences in their expectations rather than reassurance from the clinician.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Adequate time for consultation and plain language information can help parents make informed decisions and avoid unnecessary antibiotic use.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The prescriber should closely adhere to the five rights of drug administration: the right patient, the right drug, the right dose, the right route, and the right time.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Microbiological samples should be taken for culture and sensitivity testing before treatment when indicated and treatment potentially changed based on the susceptibility report.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Health workers and pharmacists can help tackle antibiotic resistance by: enhancing infection prevention and control; only prescribing and dispensing antibiotics when they are truly needed; prescribing and dispensing the right antibiotic(s) to treat the illness.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A unit dose system implemented in community pharmacies can also reduce antibiotic leftovers at households.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Despite these, written guideline intervention for prescriber to do history taking and provision of advice and knowledge of pharmacists and non‐pharmacists may not reduce the sales of non‐prescription antimicrobial drugs in community pharmacies, drugstores, and other medicine outlets.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] People can help tackle resistance by using antibiotics only when prescribed for a bacterial infetion as well as completing the full treatment course, never sharing medication with others, and using proper disposal methods for excess drugs.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Basic hygiene practices also help prevent the spread of bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] • Germany and Sweden also have lower prescribing rates, with Sweden's rate having been declining since 2007. • Greece, France and Belgium have high prescribing rates.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Infectious disease control through improved water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) infrastructure needs to be included in the antimicrobial resistance (AMR) agenda.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Growing usage of antibiotics together with persistent infectious disease levels have led to a dangerous cycle in which reliance on antimicrobials increases while the efficacy of drugs diminishes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The proper use of infrastructure for water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) can result in a 47–72 percent decrease of diarrhea cases treated with antibiotics depending on the type of intervention and its effectiveness.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A reduction of the diarrhea disease burden through improved infrastructure would result in large decreases in the number of diarrhea cases treated with antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This was estimated as ranging from 5 million in Brazil to up to 590 million in India by the year 2030.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The strong link between increased consumption and resistance indicates that this will directly mitigate the accelerating spread of AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Sanitation and water for all by 2030 is Goal Number 6 of the Sustainable Development Goals.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] An increase in hand washing compliance by hospital staff results in decreased rates of resistant organisms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Water supply and sanitation infrastructure in health facilities offer opportunities for combatting AMR, and investment should be increased.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] There is much room for improvement: WHO and UNICEF estimated in 2015 that 38% of health facilities did not have a source of water, nearly 19% had no toilets and 35% had no water and soap or alcohol-based hand rub for handwashing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Manufacturers of antimicrobials need to improve the treatment of their wastewater (by using industrial wastewater treatment processes) to reduce the release of residues into the environment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] It is established that the use of antibiotics in animal husbandry can give rise to AMR resistances in bacteria found in food animals to the antibiotics being administered (through injections or medicated feeds).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For this reason only antimicrobials that are deemed "not-clinically relevant" are used in these practices.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Unlike resistance to antibacterials, antifungal resistance can be driven by arable farming, currently there is no regulation on the use of similar antifungal classes in agriculture and the clinic.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Recent studies have shown that the prophylactic use of "non-priority" or "non-clinically relevant" antimicrobials in feeds can potentially, under certain conditions, lead to co-selection of environmental AMR bacteria with resistance to medically important antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The possibility for co-selection of AMR resistances in the food chain pipeline may have far-reaching implications for human health.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 1997, European Union health ministers voted to ban avoparcin and four additional antibiotics used to promote animal growth in 1999.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2006 a ban on the use of antibiotics in European feed, with the exception of two antibiotics in poultry feeds, became effective.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In Scandinavia, there is evidence that the ban has led to a lower prevalence of antibiotic resistance in (nonhazardous) animal bacterial populations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] As of 2004, several European countries established a decline of antimicrobial resistance in humans through limiting the use of antimicrobials in agriculture and food industries without jeopardizing animal health or economic cost.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) collect data on antibiotic use in humans and in a more limited fashion in animals.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] About 80% of antibiotic use in the U.S. is for agriculture purposes, and about 70% of these are medically important.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This gives reason for concern about the antibiotic resistance crisis in the U.S. and more reason to monitor it.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The FDA first determined in 1977 that there is evidence of emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains in livestock.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The long-established practice of permitting OTC sales of antibiotics (including penicillin and other drugs) to lay animal owners for administration to their own animals nonetheless continued in all states.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2000, the FDA announced their intention to revoke approval of fluoroquinolone use in poultry production because of substantial evidence linking it to the emergence of fluoroquinolone-resistant *Campylobacter* infections in humans.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Legal challenges from the food animal and pharmaceutical industries delayed the final decision to do so until 2006.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Fluroquinolones have been banned from extra-label use in food animals in the USA since 2007.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, they are still used in treatment of companion and exotic animals.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The increasing interconnectedness of the world and the fact that new classes of antibiotics have not been developed and approved for 25 years highlight the extent to which antimicrobial resistance is a global health challenge.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A global action plan to tackle the growing problem of resistance to antibiotics and other antimicrobial medicines was endorsed at the Sixty-eighth World Health Assembly in May 2015.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] One of the key objectives of the plan is to improve awareness and understanding of antimicrobial resistance through effective communication, education and training.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This global action plan developed by the World Health Organization was created to combat the issue of antimicrobial resistance and was guided by the advice of countries and key stakeholders.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO's global action plan is composed of five key objectives that can be targeted through different means, and represents countries coming together to solve a major problem that can have future health consequences.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The World Health Organization has promoted the first World Antibiotic Awareness Week running from 16 to 22 November 2015.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The aim of the week is to increase global awareness of antibiotic resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] It also wants to promote the correct usage of antibiotics across all fields to prevent further instances of antibiotic resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] World Antibiotic Awareness Week has been held every November since 2015.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For 2017, the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), the World Health Organization (WHO) and the World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE) are together calling for responsible use of antibiotics in humans and animals to reduce the emergence of antibiotic resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2016 the Secretary-General of the United Nations convened the Interagency Coordination Group (IACG) on Antimicrobial Resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The IACG worked with international organizations and experts in human, animal, and plant health to create a plan to fight antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Their report released in April 2019 focuses on the seriousness of antimicrobial resistance and the threat it poses to world health.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] It suggests five recommendations for member states to follow to tackle this increasing threat.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The **One Health** approach recognizes that human, animal, and environmental health are interconnected in the development and spread of antimicrobial resistance (AMR).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Alteration of target- or binding site: for example, alteration of PBP—the binding target site of penicillins—in MRSA and other penicillin-resistant bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Another protective mechanism found among bacterial species is ribosomal protection proteins.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These proteins protect the bacterial cell from antibiotics that target the cell's ribosomes to inhibit protein synthesis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The mechanism involves the binding of the ribosomal protection proteins to the ribosomes of the bacterial cell, which in turn changes its conformational shape.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This allows the ribosomes to continue synthesizing proteins essential to the cell while preventing antibiotics from binding to the ribosome to inhibit protein synthesis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Reduced drug accumulation: by decreasing drug permeability or increasing active efflux (pumping out) of the drugs across the cell surface.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These multidrug efflux pumps within the cellular membrane of certain bacterial species are used to pump antibiotics out of the cell before they are able to do any damage.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] They are often activated by a specific substrate associated with an antibiotic, as in fluoroquinolone resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Ribosome splitting and recycling: for example, drug-mediated stalling of the ribosome by lincomycin and erythromycin unstalled by a heat shock protein found in *Listeria monocytogenes*, which is a homologue of HflX from other bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Liberation of the ribosome from the drug allows further translation and consequent resistance to the drug.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] There are several different types of germs that have developed a resistance over time.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The six pathogens causing most deaths associated with resistance are *Escherichia coli*, *Staphylococcus aureus, Klebsiella pneumoniae, Streptococcus pneumoniae, Acinetobacter baumannii*, and *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] They were responsible for 929,000 deaths attributable to resistance and 3.57 million deaths associated with resistance in 2019.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Penicillinase-producing *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* developed a resistance to penicillin in 1976.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Another example is Azithromycin-resistant *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, which developed a resistance to azithromycin in 2011.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In gram-negative bacteria, plasmid-mediated resistance genes produce proteins that can bind to DNA gyrase, protecting it from the action of quinolones.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Finally, mutations at key sites in DNA gyrase or topoisomerase IV can decrease their binding affinity to quinolones, decreasing the drug's effectiveness.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some bacteria are naturally resistant to certain antibiotics; for example, gram-negative bacteria are resistant to most β-lactam antibiotics due to the presence of β-lactamase.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antibiotic resistance can also be acquired as a result of either genetic mutation or horizontal gene transfer.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Although mutations are rare, with spontaneous mutations in the pathogen genome occurring at a rate of about 1 in 105 to 1 in 108 per chromosomal replication, Bacteria reproduce at a high rate, lifespans and production of new generations can be on a timescale of mere hours.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A new (de novo) mutation in a parent cell can quickly become an inherited mutation of widespread prevalence, resulting in the microevolution of a fully resistant colony.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, chromosomal mutations also confer a cost of fitness.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For example, a ribosomal mutation may protect a bacterial cell by changing the binding site of an antibiotic but may result in slower growth rate.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Moreover, some adaptive mutations can propagate not only through inheritance but also through horizontal gene transfer.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The most common mechanism of horizontal gene transfer is the transferring of plasmids carrying antibiotic resistance genes between bacteria of the same or different species via conjugation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Recent findings show no necessity of large populations of bacteria for the appearance of antibiotic resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Small populations of *Escherichia coli* in an antibiotic gradient can become resistant.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Any heterogeneous environment with respect to nutrient and antibiotic gradients may facilitate antibiotic resistance in small bacterial populations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Researchers hypothesize that the mechanism of resistance evolution is based on four SNP mutations in the genome of *E. coli* produced by the gradient of antibiotic.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In one study, which has implications for space microbiology, a non-pathogenic strain *E. coli* MG1655 was exposed to trace levels of the broad spectrum antibiotic chloramphenicol, under simulated microgravity (LSMMG, or Low Shear Modeled Microgravity) over 1000 generations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Thus, irrespective of where they are used, the use of an antibiotic would likely result in persistent resistance to that antibiotic, as well as cross-resistance to other antimicrobials.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In recent years, the emergence and spread of β-lactamases called carbapenemases has become a major health crisis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] One such carbapenemase is New Delhi metallo-beta-lactamase 1 (NDM-1), an enzyme that makes bacteria resistant to a broad range of beta-lactam antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The most common bacteria that make this enzyme are gram-negative such as *E. coli* and *Klebsiella pneumoniae*, but the gene for NDM-1 can spread from one strain of bacteria to another by horizontal gene transfer.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Specific antiviral drugs are used to treat some viral infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These drugs prevent viruses from reproducing by inhibiting essential stages of the virus's replication cycle in infected cells.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antivirals are used to treat HIV, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, influenza, herpes viruses including varicella zoster virus, cytomegalovirus and Epstein–Barr virus.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] With each virus, some strains have become resistant to the administered drugs.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antiviral drugs typically target key components of viral reproduction; for example, oseltamivir targets influenza neuraminidase,while guanosine analogs inhibit viral DNA polymerase.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to antivirals is thus acquired through mutations in the genes that encode the protein targets of the drugs.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to HIV antivirals is problematic, and even multi-drug resistant strains have evolved.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] One source of resistance is that many current HIV drugs, including NRTIs and NNRTIs, target reverse transcriptase; however, HIV-1 reverse transcriptase is highly error prone and thus mutations conferring resistance arise rapidly.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistant strains of the HIV virus emerge rapidly if only one antiviral drug is used.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Using three or more drugs together, termed combination therapy, has helped to control this problem, but new drugs are needed because of the continuing emergence of drug-resistant HIV strains.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Infections by fungi are a cause of high morbidity and mortality in immunocompromised persons, such as those with HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis or receiving chemotherapy.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The fungi *Candida*, *Cryptococcus neoformans* and *Aspergillus fumigatus* cause most of these infections and antifungal resistance occurs in all of them.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Multidrug resistance in fungi is increasing because of the widespread use of antifungal drugs to treat infections in immunocompromised individuals and the use of some agricultural antifungals.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antifungal resistant disease is associated with increased mortality.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some fungi (for example, *Candida krusei* and fluconazole) exhibit intrinsic resistance to certain antifungal drugs or classes, whereas some species develop antifungal resistance to external pressures.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antifungal resistance is a One Health concern, driven by multiple extrinsic factors, including overuse of fungicides, clinical antifungals, environmental change and host factors.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In the USA fluconazole-resistant Candida species and azole resistance in Aspergillus fumigatus have been highlighted as a growing threat.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] 20 species of *Candida* can cause candidiasis infection, the most common of which is *Candida albicans*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] *Candida* yeasts normally inhabit the skin and mucous membranes without causing infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, overgrowth of *Candida* can lead to candidiasis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] *Candida glabrata)* are becoming resistant to first-line and second-line antifungal agents such as echinocandins and azoles.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The emergence of *Candida auris* as a potential human pathogen that sometimes exhibits multi-class antifungal drug resistance is concerning and has been associated with several outbreaks.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO has released a priority fungal pathogen list, including pathogens with antifungal resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The identification of antifungal resistance is undermined by limited classical diagnosis of infection, where a culture is lacking, preventing susceptibility testing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] National and international surveillance schemes for fungal disease and antifungal resistance are limited, hampering the understanding of the disease burden and associated resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The application of molecular testing to identify genetic markers associating with resistance may improve the identification of antifungal resistance, but the diversity of mutations associated with resistance is increasing across the fungal species causing infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In addition, a number of resistance mechanisms depend on up-regulation of selected genes (for instance reflux pumps) rather than defined mutations that are amenable to molecular detection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Due to the limited number of antifungals in clinical use and the increasing global incidence of antifungal resistance, using the existing antifungals in combination might be beneficial in some cases but further research is needed.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Similarly, other approaches that might help to combat the emergence of antifungal resistance could rely on the development of host-directed therapies such as immunotherapy or vaccines.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The protozoan parasites that cause the diseases malaria, trypanosomiasis, toxoplasmosis, cryptosporidiosis and leishmaniasis are important human pathogens.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Malarial parasites that are resistant to the drugs that are currently available to infections are common and this has led to increased efforts to develop new drugs.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to recently developed drugs such as artemisinin has also been reported.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The problem of drug resistance in malaria has driven efforts to develop vaccines.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Trypanosomes are parasitic protozoa that cause African trypanosomiasis and Chagas disease (American trypanosomiasis).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] There are no vaccines to prevent these infections so drugs such as pentamidine and suramin, benznidazole and nifurtimox are used to treat infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] These drugs are effective but infections caused by resistant parasites have been reported.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Leishmaniasis is caused by protozoa and is a public health problem in sub-tropical and tropical countries.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Drug resistance has "become a major concern".
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The preferred treatment for leishmaniasis regionally; liposomal amphotericin B is used in the Mediterranean basin and pentavalent antimonials are more commonly used in Africa, South America, Bangladesh, India, and Nepal.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Resistance to antibiotics in *Leishmania* is a relatively recent phenomena.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The first reported instance of resistance to antimonials was reported in India in the 1980s.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2022, genomic epidemiologists reported results from a global survey of antimicrobial resistance via genomic wastewater-based epidemiology, finding large regional variations, providing maps, and suggesting resistance genes are also passed on between microbial species that are not closely related.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The WHO provides the Global Antimicrobial Resistance and Use Surveillance System (GLASS) reports which summarize annual (e.g.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] 2020's) data on international AMR, also including an interactive dashboard.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Public Health England reported that the total number of antibiotic resistant infections in England rose by 9% from 55,812 in 2017 to 60,788 in 2018, but antibiotic consumption had fallen by 9% from 20.0 to 18.2 defined daily doses per 1,000 inhabitants per day between 2014 and 2018.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported that 2.8 million cases of antibiotic resistance have been reported.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, in 2019 overall deaths from antibiotic-resistant infections decreased by 18% and deaths in hospitals decreased by 30%.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The COVID pandemic caused a reversal of much of the progress made on attenuating the effects of antibiotic resistance, resulting in more antibiotic use, more resistant infections, and less data on preventive action.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Hospital-onset infections and deaths both increased by 15% in 2020, and significantly higher rates of infections were reported for 4 out of 6 types of healthcare associated infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Owing to rampant misuse, over-prescription, and unregulated over-the-counter access to antibiotics, the growth of AMR superbugs has proliferated in India.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Pharmacies surveyed by the Karnataka government revealed that 80% of drugs were being sold without a prescription.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2019, India reported 300,000 deaths because of infections relating to AMR, India also reports the most number of tuberculosis cases resistant to antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The 1950s to 1970s represented the golden age of antibiotic discovery, where countless new classes of antibiotics were discovered to treat previously incurable diseases such as tuberculosis and syphilis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] However, since that time the discovery of new classes of antibiotics has been almost nonexistent, and represents a situation that is especially problematic considering the resiliency of bacteria shown over time and the continued misuse and overuse of antibiotics in treatment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Already in 1940, in their letter to the editor of Nature journal, Abraham and Chain identified the enzyme penicillinase as responsible for the deactivation of penicillin in penicillin-resistant bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This discovery was the first step in understanding the mechanisms of microbial resistance to β-lactam antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The phenomenon of antimicrobial resistance caused by overuse of antibiotics was predicted as early as 1945 by Alexander Fleming who said "The time may come when penicillin can be bought by anyone in the shops.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Antimicrobial resistance can lead to epidemics of enormous proportions if preventive actions are not taken.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In this day and age current antimicrobial resistance leads to longer hospital stays, higher medical costs, and increased mortality.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Since the mid-1980s pharmaceutical companies have invested in medications for cancer or chronic disease that have greater potential to make money and have "de-emphasized or dropped development of antibiotics".
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] On 20 January 2016 at the World Economic Forum, "80 pharmaceutical and diagnostic companies" called for "transformational commercial models" at an international level to spur research and development on antibiotics and on the use of diagnostic tests.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A number of countries are considering or implementing delinked payment models for new antimicrobials whereby payment is based on value rather than volume of drug sales.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This offers the opportunity to pay for valuable new drugs even if they are reserved for use in relatively rare drug resistant infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Some global health scholars have argued that a global, legal framework is needed to prevent and control antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For instance, binding global policies could be used to create antimicrobial use standards, regulate antibiotic marketing, and strengthen global surveillance systems.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Ensuring compliance of involved parties is a challenge.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] For the United States 2016 budget, U.S. president Barack Obama proposed to nearly double the amount of federal funding to "combat and prevent" antibiotic resistance to $1.2 billion.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Many international funding agencies like USAID, DFID, Sida and Gates Foundation have pledged money for developing strategies to counter antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] On 27 March 2015, the White House released a plan to address the increasing need for agencies to combat the rise of antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Task Force for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria developed *The National Action Plan for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria* with the intent of providing a roadmap to guide the US in the antibiotic resistance challenge and with hopes of saving many lives.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This plan outlines steps taken by the Federal government over the next five years needed to prevent and contain outbreaks of antibiotic-resistant infections; maintain the efficacy of antibiotics already on the market; and to help to develop future diagnostics, antibiotics, and vaccines.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Action Plan was developed around five goals with focuses on strengthening health care, public health veterinary medicine, agriculture, food safety and research, and manufacturing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] As of 2023, AMR remains a public health threat in the United States.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's 2023 Report on Antibiotic Resistance Threats, over 2.8 million antibiotic-resistant infections occur in the U.S. each year, leading to at least 35,000 deaths annually.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Among the most concerning resistant pathogens are Carbapenem-resistant *Enterobacteriaceae* (CRE), Methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA), and *Clostridioides difficile* (C. diff), all of which continue to be responsible for severe healthcare-associated infections (HAIs).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic led to a disruption in healthcare, with an increase in the use of antibiotics during the treatment of viral infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This rise in antibiotic prescribing, coupled with overwhelmed healthcare systems, contributed to a resurgence in AMR during the pandemic years.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] A 2021 CDC report identified a sharp increase in HAIs caused by resistant pathogens in COVID-19 patients, a trend that has persisted into 2023.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Recent data suggest that although antibiotic use has decreased since the pandemic, some resistant pathogens remain prevalent in healthcare settings.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The CDC has also expanded its Get Ahead of Sepsis campaign in 2023, focusing on raising awareness of AMR's role in sepsis and promoting the judicious use of antibiotics in both healthcare and community settings.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This initiative has reached millions through social media, healthcare facilities, and public health outreach, aiming to educate the public on the importance of preventing infections and reducing antibiotic misuse.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Trump, severe federal funding cuts in 2025 at the National Institutes of Health (NIH) and many other research entities in the United States are expected to impede progress in combating antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Public health experts believe these budget reductions will adversely affect the development of new antibiotics as well as advances in diagnostics and treatment strategies, thus undermining efforts currently underway to address AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The Infectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) is but one organization that has expressed grave concern regarding the negative consequences of such extreme budget measures on antimicrobial stewardship, and, as a result, on global health security overall.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] According to World Health Organization, policymakers can help tackle resistance by strengthening resistance-tracking and laboratory capacity and by regulating and promoting the appropriate use of medicines.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Policymakers and industry can help tackle resistance by: fostering research and development of new tools and promoting cooperation and information sharing among all stakeholders.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The U.S. government continues to prioritize AMR mitigation through policy and legislation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In 2023, the National Action Plan for Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria (CARB) 2023-2028 was released, outlining strategic objectives for reducing antibiotic-resistant infections, advancing infection prevention, and accelerating research on new antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] The plan also emphasizes the importance of improving antibiotic stewardship across healthcare, agriculture, and veterinary settings.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Furthermore, the PASTEUR Act (Pioneering Antimicrobial Subscriptions to End Upsurging Resistance) has gained momentum in Congress.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] If passed, the bill would create a subscription-based payment model to incentivize the development of new antimicrobial drugs, while supporting antimicrobial stewardship programs to reduce the misuse of existing antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] This legislation is considered a critical step toward addressing the economic barriers to developing new antimicrobials.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] Measuring the costs and benefits of strategies to combat AMR is difficult and policies may only have effects in the distant future.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] In other infectious diseases this problem has been addressed by using mathematical models.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p02] More research is needed to understand how AMR develops and spreads so that mathematical modelling can be used to anticipate the likely effects of different policies.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Distinguishing infections requiring antibiotics from self-limiting ones is clinically challenging.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] To guide appropriate use of antibiotics and prevent the evolution and spread of antimicrobial resistance, diagnostic tests that provide clinicians with timely, actionable results are needed.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Acute fever is a common reason for seeking medical care and a major cause of morbidity and mortality.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Multiple studies have shown that the use of malaria rapid diagnostic tests without reliable tools to distinguish other fever causes has resulted in increased antibiotic use.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Antimicrobial susceptibility testing (AST) can facilitate a precision medicine approach to treatment by helping clinicians to prescribe more effective and targeted antimicrobial therapy.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] At the same time with traditional phenotypic AST it can take 12 to 48 hours to obtain a result due to the time taken for organisms to grow on/in culture media.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Rapid testing, possible from molecular diagnostics innovations, is defined as "being feasible within an 8-h working shift".
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] There are several commercial Food and Drug Administration-approved assays available which can detect AMR genes from a variety of specimen types.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Progress has been slow due to a range of reasons including cost and regulation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Genotypic AMR characterisation methods are, however, being increasingly used in combination with machine learning algorithms in research to help better predict phenotypic AMR from organism genotype.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Optical techniques such as phase contrast microscopy in combination with single-cell analysis are another powerful method to monitor bacterial growth.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In 2017, scientists from Uppsala University in Sweden published a method that applies principles of microfluidics and cell tracking, to monitor bacterial response to antibiotics in less than 30 minutes overall manipulation time.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] This invention was awarded the 8M£ Longitude Prize on AMR in 2024.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Recently, this platform has been advanced by coupling microfluidic chip with optical tweezing to isolate bacteria with altered phenotype directly from the analytical matrix.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Rapid diagnostic methods have also been trialled as antimicrobial stewardship interventions to influence the healthcare drivers of AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Serum procalcitonin measurement has been shown to reduce mortality rate, antimicrobial consumption and antimicrobial-related side-effects in patients with respiratory infections, but impact on AMR has not yet been demonstrated.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Similarly, point of care serum testing of the inflammatory biomarker C-reactive protein has been shown to influence antimicrobial prescribing rates in this patient cohort, but further research is required to demonstrate an effect on rates of AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Clinical investigation to rule out bacterial infections are often done for patients with pediatric acute respiratory infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Currently it is unclear if rapid viral testing affects antibiotic use in children.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Vaccines are an essential part of the response to reduce AMR as they prevent infections, reduce the use and overuse of antimicrobials, and slow the emergence and spread of drug-resistant pathogens.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Microorganisms usually do not develop resistance to vaccines because vaccines reduce the spread of the infection and target the pathogen in multiple ways in the same host and possibly in different ways between different hosts.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Furthermore, if the use of vaccines increases, there is evidence that antibiotic resistant strains of pathogens will decrease; the need for antibiotics will naturally decrease as vaccines prevent infection before it occurs.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] A 2024 report by WHO finds that vaccines against 24 pathogens could reduce the number of antibiotics needed by 22% or 2.5 billion DDD every year.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] If vaccines could be rolled out against all the evaluated pathogens, they could save a third of the hospital costs associated with AMR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Vaccinated people have fewer infections and are protected against potential complications from secondary infections that may need antimicrobial medicines or require admission to hospital.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] However, there are well documented cases of vaccine resistance, although these are usually much less of a problem than antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Antistaphylococcal vaccines have shown limited efficacy, because of immunological variation between *Staphylococcus* species, and the limited duration of effectiveness of the antibodies produced.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Development and testing of more effective vaccines is underway.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Two registrational trials have evaluated vaccine candidates in active immunization strategies against *S. aureus* infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In a phase II trial, a bivalent vaccine of capsular proteins 5 & 8 was tested in 1804 hemodialysis patients with a primary fistula or synthetic graft vascular access.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] After 40 weeks following vaccination a protective effect was seen against *S. aureus* bacteremia, but not at 54 weeks following vaccination.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Based on these results, a second trial was conducted which failed to show efficacy.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Merck tested V710, a vaccine targeting IsdB, in a blinded randomized trial in patients undergoing median sternotomy.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The trial was terminated after a higher rate of multiorgan system failure–related deaths was found in the V710 recipients.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Vaccine recipients who developed *S. aureus* infection were five times more likely to die than control recipients who developed *S. aureus* infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Investigators have suggested that a multiple-antigen vaccine would be more effective, but a lack of biomarkers defining human protective immunity keep these proposals in the logical, but strictly hypothetical arena.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Antibodies show evidence against antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Monoclonal antibodies (mAbs) target bacterial virulence factors, aiding in bacterial destruction through various mechanisms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Three FDA-approved antibodies target *Bacillus anthracis* and *Clostridioides difficile* toxins.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Alternating therapy is a proposed method in which two or three antibiotics are taken in a rotation versus taking just one antibiotic such that bacteria resistant to one antibiotic are killed when the next antibiotic is taken.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Studies have found that this method reduces the rate at which antibiotic resistant bacteria emerge in vitro relative to a single drug for the entire duration.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Studies have found that bacteria that evolve antibiotic resistance towards one group of antibiotic may become more sensitive to others.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] This phenomenon can be used to select against resistant bacteria using an approach termed collateral sensitivity cycling, which has recently been found to be relevant in developing treatment strategies for chronic infections caused by *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Despite its promise, large-scale clinical and experimental studies revealed limited evidence of susceptibility to antibiotic cycling across various pathogens.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Another concern is that practitioners may become reluctant to perform routine surgeries because of the increased risk of harmful infection.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Backup treatments can have serious side-effects; for example, antibiotics like aminoglycosides (such as amikacin, gentamicin, kanamycin, streptomycin, etc.) used for the treatment of drug-resistant tuberculosis and cystic fibrosis can cause respiratory disorders, deafness and kidney failure.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The potential crisis at hand is the result of a marked decrease in industry research and development.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Poor financial investment in antibiotic research has exacerbated the situation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In 2011, Pfizer, one of the last major pharmaceutical companies developing new antibiotics, shut down its primary research effort, citing poor shareholder returns relative to drugs for chronic illnesses.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] However, small and medium-sized pharmaceutical companies are still active in antibiotic drug research.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In particular, apart from classical synthetic chemistry methodologies, researchers have developed a combinatorial synthetic biology platform on single cell level in a high-throughput screening manner to diversify novel lanthipeptides.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In the 5–10 years since 2010, there has been a change in the ways new antimicrobial agents are discovered and developed – principally via the formation of public-private funding initiatives.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Later stage clinical development is supported by the AMR Action Fund, which in turn is supported by multiple investors with the aim of developing 2–4 new antimicrobial agents by 2030.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The discovery and development of new antimicrobial agents has been facilitated by regulatory advances, which have been principally led by the European Medicines Agency (EMA) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] These processes are increasingly aligned although important differences remain and drug developers must prepare separate documents.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] New development pathways have been developed to help with the approval of new antimicrobial agents that address unmet needs such as the Limited Population Pathway for Antibacterial and Antifungal Drugs (LPAD).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] These new pathways are required because of difficulties in conducting large definitive phase III clinical trials in a timely way.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Some of the economic impediments to the development of new antimicrobial agents have been addressed by reimbursement schemes that delink payment of antimicrobials from volume-based sales.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The available classes of antifungal drugs are still limited but as of 2021 novel classes of antifungals are being developed and are undergoing various stages of clinical trials to assess performance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Scientists have started using advanced computational approaches with supercomputers for the development of new antibiotic derivatives to deal with antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Using antibiotic-free alternatives in bone infection treatment may help decrease the use of antibiotics and thus antimicrobial resistance.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The bone regeneration material bioactive glass S53P4 has shown to effectively inhibit the bacterial growth of up to 50 clinically relevant bacteria including MRSA and MRSE.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] During the last decades, copper and silver nanomaterials have demonstrated appealing features for the development of a new family of antimicrobial agents.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Nanoparticles (1–100 nm) show unique properties and promise as antimicrobial agents against resistant bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Silver (AgNPs) and gold nanoparticles (AuNPs) are extensively studied, disrupting bacterial cell membranes and interfering with protein synthesis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Zinc oxide (ZnO NPs), copper (CuNPs), and silica (SiNPs) nanoparticles also exhibit antimicrobial properties.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] However, high synthesis costs, potential toxicity, and instability pose challenges.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] To overcome these, biological synthesis methods and combination therapies with other antimicrobials are explored.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Similar to the situation in malaria therapy, where successful treatments based on ancient recipes have been found, there has already been some success in finding and testing ancient drugs and other treatments that are effective against AMR bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] One of the key tools identified by the WHO and others for the fight against rising antimicrobial resistance is improved surveillance of the spread and movement of AMR genes through different communities and regions.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Recent advances in high-throughput DNA sequencing as a result of the Human Genome Project have resulted in the ability to determine the individual microbial genes in a sample.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Along with the availability of databases of known antimicrobial resistance genes, such as the Comprehensive Antimicrobial Resistance Database (CARD) and ResFinder, this allows the identification of all the antimicrobial resistance genes within the sample – the so-called "resistome".
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In doing so, a profile of these genes within a community or environment can be determined, providing information into how antimicrobial resistance is spreading through a population and allowing for the identification of resistance that is of concern.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phage therapy is the therapeutic use of bacteriophages to treat pathogenic bacterial infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phage therapy has many potential applications in human medicine as well as dentistry, veterinary science, and agriculture.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phage therapy relies on the use of naturally occurring bacteriophages to infect and lyse bacteria at the site of infection in a host.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Due to current advances in genetics and biotechnology these bacteriophages can possibly be manufactured to treat specific infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phages can be bioengineered to target multidrug-resistant bacterial infections, and their use involves the added benefit of preventing the elimination of beneficial bacteria in the human body.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Phages destroy bacterial cell walls and membrane through the use of lytic proteins which kill bacteria by making many holes from the inside out.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bacteriophages can even possess the ability to digest the biofilm that many bacteria develop that protect them from antibiotics to effectively infect and kill bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bioengineering can play a role in creating successful bacteriophages.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Understanding the mutual interactions and evolutions of bacterial and phage populations in the environment of a human or animal body is essential for rational phage therapy.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bacteriophagics are used against antibiotic resistant bacteria in Georgia (George Eliava Institute) and in one institute in Wrocław, Poland.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Bacteriophage cocktails are common drugs sold over the counter in pharmacies in eastern countries.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] In Belgium, four patients with severe musculoskeletal infections received bacteriophage therapy with concomitant antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] After a single course of phage therapy, no recurrence of infection occurred and no severe side-effects related to the therapy were detected.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Analysing AMR data at scale requires dedicated computational approaches, as routine microbiological data from clinical laboratories can be large, heterogeneous, and subject to varying local standards.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] Several open-source tools have been developed to support this work.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/antimicrobial-resistance-p03] The AMR package for R provides functions for standardising and analysing phenotypical resistance data, including interpretation of MIC and disk diffusion results against EUCAST and CLSI breakpoints, and calculation of resistance rates across patient populations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma is thought to be caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Environmental factors include exposure to air pollution and allergens.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Other potential triggers include medications such as aspirin and beta blockers.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Diagnosis is usually based on the pattern of symptoms, response to therapy over time, and spirometry lung function testing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma is classified according to the amount of medication required to control symptoms or mechanisms underlying the condition.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] There is no known cure for asthma, but it can be controlled.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Symptoms can be prevented by avoiding triggers, such as allergens and respiratory irritants, and suppressed with the use of inhaled corticosteroids.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Long-acting beta agonists (LABA) or antileukotriene agents may be used in addition to inhaled corticosteroids if asthma symptoms remain uncontrolled.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Treatment of rapidly worsening symptoms is usually with an inhaled short-acting beta2 agonist such as salbutamol, corticosteroids taken by mouth, and oxygen therapy.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In very severe cases, intravenous corticosteroids and hospitalization may be required.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In 2023, asthma affected an estimated 363 million people worldwide and caused 442,000 deaths.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Most asthma-related deaths occur in low- and lower-middle-income countries.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma was recognized as early as ancient egypt.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The word *asthma* is from the Greek ἆσθμα (*âsthma*), which means 'panting'.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma causes recurrent episodes of wheezing, shortness of breath, chest tightness, and coughing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Symptoms are usually worse at night and in the early morning or in response to exercise or cold air.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Some people with asthma rarely experience symptoms, usually in response to triggers, whereas others may react frequently and experience persistent symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma is often associated with other conditions both within and outside of the respiratory system.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Comorbid medical conditions are more common in severe asthma and can affect the disease severity, symptoms and treatment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Due to the diversity in onset, symptoms, outcomes, and response to treatment, asthma is often considered a syndrome — a collection of signs and symptoms — rather than a single condition.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Historically asthma was classified as being caused by external factors (extrinsic) such as allergens or by internal factors (intrinsic), unrelated to allergies.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Currently asthma is most commonly classified according to severity, control of symptoms, phenotypes and endotypes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) cause airway restriction and have a wide range of overlapping mechanisms and symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The main difference between the two disorders is that in asthma expiratory airflow fluctuates over time while in COPD airflow obstruction is chronic and often increases in severity over time.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma severity is determined on the basis of how much medication is required to control symptoms and exacerbations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma control is the burden of asthma on an individual such as symptoms and inflammation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Classification of asthma control does not depend on medication usage like severity does, however they often assess similar factors.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma control is assessed based on how well the symptoms are being controlled and future risk of consequences of the disorder.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The frequency and severity of symptoms, impairment caused by symptoms, use of rescue inhalers, questionnaires, healthcare usage, and objective tests such as spirometry, FeNO, sputum eosinophils, and hyperresponsiveness studies are used to evaluate asthma control.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma severity is measured based on how difficult the disorder is to treat.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Severity can only be measured once the disorder is under control.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Those with mild asthma may only require as needed medication to treat the disease while those with severe asthma require high doses of medication to gain control over the disorder or may be unable to get their symptoms under control even with medications.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] A phenotype is the way in which a condition presents itself, such as when the disease first starts to affect a person and what symptoms an individual displays.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] An endotype is the mechanisms that underlie the condition.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma is most commonly divided into two endotypes, T2-high and T2-low (non-T2).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Within the two main endotypes there are subpopulations (phenotypes), some of which overlap or can be categorized under both of the two endotypes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The two endotypes are distinguished based on the type of inflammation present, with the type-2 high endotype involving the type 2 immune system response and type-2 low involving type 1 immune system response.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Type-2 high is characterized by increased eosinophils, increased Fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO), or allergens.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Type-2 low asthma is the absence of these inflammatory markers and the mechanisms are not well researched.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The phenotypes included under the type-2 high endotype include early-onset allergic asthma, late-onset eosinophilic asthma, and Aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Type-2 low asthma phenotypes include asthma associated with obesity, neutrophilic asthma, asthma associated with cigarette smoke, and paucigranulocytic asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Occupational asthma can be further split into separate phenotypes, irritant-induced asthma — caused by exposure to airway irritants such as cleaning products and dust — and sensitizer-induced occupational asthma — developed hypersensitivity.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Irritant-induced asthma is a type-2 low phenotype while sensitizer-induced occupational asthma is a type-2 high phenotype.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma-COPD overlap (ACO) currently lacks a consistent definition making it hard to categorize it into either endotype.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] An asthma exacerbation, commonly referred to as an **asthma attack**, asthma episode, or acute severe asthma are episodes of increased symptoms (shortness of breath, wheezing, coughing, chest tightness), and decreased lung function.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Decreased lung function is measured by peak expiratory flow rate (PEF) or forced expiratory volume in 1 second.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Signs occurring during an asthma exacerbation include the use of accessory muscles of respiration (sternocleidomastoid and scalene muscles), chest retractions with breathing, blue colour of the skin and nails, increased heart rate and changes in respiratory sounds.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] An asthma exacerbation is considered mild when there is difficulty carrying out daily activities due to symptoms and a decrease of at least 20% in PEF for over two days.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In moderate exacerbations, oxygen desaturation is mild, there is no use of auxiliary respiratory muscles, and there is a 50% or lower decrease in PEF.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] During severe exacerbations, the person experiencing symptoms becomes restless and may struggle to speak; oxygen saturation drops and there is above a 50% decrease in PEF.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Life-threatening exacerbations cause lethargy and clouding of consciousness.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Brittle asthma is a kind of asthma distinguishable by recurrent, severe attacks.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] However, brittle asthma is best regarded as a historical disease descriptor rather than a distinct diagnostic category.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] While it remains useful for understanding older literature it is no longer routinely used in contemporary clinical practice.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma is caused by a mixture of genetic and external factors.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The disease manifests when those with a genetic susceptibility to asthma are exposed to specific environmental factors.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Environmental factors can also trigger asthma symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Factors during pregnancy that have been linked to the development of asthma include weight gain or obesity in the mother, stressful pregnancy, smoking while pregnant, the use of certain medications while pregnant and caesarean section.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Early childhood exposure to secondhand smoke, high levels of stress in parents, respiratory infections, and indoor mold or fungi have also been associated with asthma development.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Prenatal or childhood exposure to cigarette smoke increases the likelihood of a child developing asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Children whose maternal grandmother smoked during pregnancy are also more likely to develop asthma, regardless of if their mothers developed asthma or smoked.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Nicotine is believed to be the cause of these effects and nicotine is linked to changes in DNA.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Respiratory tract infections, especially during early childhood or if they are severe and recurring can lead to decreased lung function and subsequent asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Conversely, there has been research suggesting that certain infections during childhood may lessen the risk of developing asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] This theory is known as the "hygiene hypothesis".
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Chronic exposure to air pollution increases the risk of developing asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Outdoor air pollution includes nitrogen dioxide and traffic pollution while indoor air pollution includes biomass, pesticides, building materials such as asbestos and formaldehyde, mold, dust mites, cockroaches, and endotoxins.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma is more commonly seen in urban environments than in rural environments.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In those who are affected by allergies, exposure to allergens can trigger asthma symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] However, some research has suggested that early exposure to allergens in childhood may help desensitize individuals from allergies.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Other studies have shown that early exposure may increase risk of allergies and the development of allergies is multifactorial.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Food allergies and atopic dermatitis in early childhood have been associated with an increased risk of developing asthma as a part of the atopic march.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Allergens also play a role in the development of adult-onset asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Adult-onset asthma is caused by relations between genetics, lifestyle factors such as obesity and smoking, and environmental factors such as an urban or rural environment, occupational exposures, and air pollution.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Unlike childhood asthma, which is more prevalent in males, in adults asthma is more prevalent in females.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Over 400 occupational exposure have been linked to asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Exposure to asthmagens, allergens and substances that are known to cause asthma; the amount and length of time that an individual was exposed to the substance; genetics; allergies; and smoking can affect the development of occupational asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma is highly polygenic, with hundreds of common and rare genetic variants of small effect contributing to disease susceptibility, age of onset, and inflammatory phenotypes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Twin studies and family studies support a substantial heritable component, with estimates that roughly half or more of asthma susceptibility is explained by genetics that is further modulated by environmental and epigenetic factors.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Large genome-wide association studies (GWAS) and sequencing efforts indicate that risk reflects the cumulative effects of numerous common genetic variants together with a more limited contribution from rare variants, rather than a small number of loci of large effect.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Meta-analyses now report over 200 genome-wide significant susceptibility loci, many mapping to immune and epithelial genes and explaining a measurable, though still incomplete, fraction of heritability.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Pathway analyses consistently highlight type 2 inflammation, epithelial barrier function, and both innate and adaptive immune signalling, including loci near or within IL33, IL1RL1/IL18R1, TSLP, MHC class II, and GATA3.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The chromosome region 17q12–21 remains the most robustly replicated asthma locus, with effects strongest for childhood-onset disease.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Multiple genes in this region, including ORMDL3 and GSDMB, appear to act primarily through regulatory mechanisms, with gene-environment interactions and age-dependent effects on airway epithelial responses, particularly to early-life viral infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Genetic correlation analyses demonstrate substantial overlap between asthma and other atopic disorders such as eczema and allergic rhinitis, as well as with lung function traits.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Multi-trait studies identify shared risk genes across asthma, hay fever, and eczema, supporting partially common pathways involving type 2 immunity and epithelial barrier dysfunction.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Consistent with this architecture, polygenic risk scores (PRS) derived from multi-ancestry GWAS can stratify individuals by asthma risk, with higher predictive performance for childhood-onset than adult-onset disease.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Individuals in the highest PRS percentiles show several-fold increased odds of childhood asthma, and PRS analyses have helped delineate heterogeneity across asthma–COPD overlap and related comorbid traits, although clinical implementation remains investigational.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Many asthma-associated variants act within regulatory elements, with effects that are highly cell-type specific and modulated by environmental exposures such as allergens, air pollution, and respiratory infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma exacerbations are commonly triggered by external factors or underusage of inhaled corticosteroid medications, however exacerbations can be sudden and unexplained.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Triggers for asthma exacerbations include viral respiratory infections, exposure to allergens, food allergies, outdoor air pollution, season changes or back to school season in the fall, lack of adherence to inhaled corticosteroids, and epidemics of severe asthma exacerbations in a community.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The mechanisms underlying asthma and asthma symptoms include spasms in the bronchial muscles, inflammation in the airways, hypersensitive airways, and excessive secretion of mucus in the airways.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma mainly affects medium-sized airways, however small or large airways may also be affected as the condition progresses.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Airway inflammation is consistent across everyone with asthma, regardless of symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The cells involved in the inflammation seen in asthma include eosinophils, neutrophils, CD4 T lymphocytes, mast cells, basophils, macrophages, respiratory epithelium, endothelial, and smooth muscle cells.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Airway inflammation leads to structural changes in the airways, including thickening of the airway smooth muscle and the tissue beneath the lining.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] There is increased tissue and matrix buildup in the airway wall, along with more small blood vessels and nerve fibers.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The glands that produce mucus also increase in size.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In asthma, the airways contract more than what is normal in response to both internal and external triggers.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] This hyperresponsiveness alongside inflammation affects the nerves in the airways — making them more sensitive — and causes the body to produce too much mucus.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Contraction of airway smooth muscle, swelling (edema), thickening of the airway wall due to remodelling, increased mucus production, and mucus plugs contribute to narrowing of the airways.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Airway hyperresponsiveness is excessive narrowing of the airways in response to stimuli that are normally harmless.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] This narrowing leads to variable airflow restriction and asthma symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Airway hyperresponsiveness is somewhat reversible with treatment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Diagnostic guidelines for asthma vary in regards to what testing should be done to confirm the diagnosis, when to test, and what criteria should be used for the diagnosis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The diagnosis cannot be made based on a single test and is instead made based on a combination of symptoms and respiratory function testing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma guidelines advise using objective tests to confirm asthma in people with suggestive symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Respiratory tests such as spirometry, bronchodilator reversibility (BDR) testing, and measuring changes in breathing flow over time (peak flow variability) are included in all major asthma guidelines.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Symptoms of wheezing, shortness of breath, chest tightness, and coughing that fluctuate according to time of day and exposure to triggers are characteristic of asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Personal or family history of allergic conditions can also help identify people with asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma rarely presents with physical findings on examination unless the person is symptomatic.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] If someone is medically unwell or displays a high amount of symptoms before the diagnosis is confirmed, medical guidelines recommend treating the person before performing respiratory testing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Global Initiative for Asthma (GINA) guidelines for children above five years of age and adults suggest confirming variable expiratory airflow in those who have symptoms suggestive of asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Variable expiratory airflow in asthma refers to fluctuations in lung function over time.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Variation in lung function can be shown by spirometry testing, peak expiratory flow, or bronchial provocation testing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The most accurate measurement of lung function is spirometry, which tests how much air a person can forcefully breathe out in one second (FEV1), FEV1 is then compared to the total amount of air exhaled after taking a deep breath (FEV1/FVC ratio).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] When testing for asthma, spirometry is performed twice; the first measurements are taken when the patient is not using any asthma medication and the second is taken after the administration of medication.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] An increase of FEV1 after taking asthma medication is indicative of asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] If spirometry is not available then peak expiratory flow can be used to show variable lung function.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] GINA guidelines recommend testing how fast a person can breathe out (peak expiratory flow) twice a day for two weeks.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Daily changes greater than 10% may suggest asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Bronchial provocation testing measures how sensitive and reactive the airways are.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] During the test, substances such as inhaled methacholine, histamine, or inhaled mannitol as well as exercise and controlled rapid breathing are used to try to trigger airway narrowing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] These tests can help identify asthma but are not specific, because airway sensitivity can also occur in other conditions like allergic rhinitis, cystic fibrosis, bronchopulmonary dysplasia, and COPD.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] A negative test result in someone not using inhaled corticosteroids (ICS) can help rule out asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] However, a positive result does not always confirm asthma, so symptoms and other clinical findings must also be considered.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] For adults, NICE guidelines recommend testing fractional exhaled nitric oxide (FeNO) and blood eosinophils as a first step.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] If FeNO or eosinophils are not elevated then they recommend testing bronchodilator reversibility (BDR) with spirometry or peak expiratory flow (PEF) if spirometry is not available.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Finally, if testing remains inconclusive, bronchial challenge tests are recommended.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Guidelines for children ages five to sixteen are similar to the adult guidelines aside from recommendations surrounding blood eosinophil count.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] For children ages five to sixteen NICE guidelines do not recommend blood eosinophil count as an initial test, but instead they recommend measuring blood eosinophil count, skin prick testing for dust mites, or total IgE levels if respiratory testing is inconclusive.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] According to NICE guidelines, children younger than five should be treated for asthma if they have symptoms suggestive of the condition instead of undergoing testing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] GINA has proposed a set of diagnostic criteria for asthma in those under the age of five.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Lack of alternative explanation for symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Response to asthma medication during acute wheezing episodes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Several conditions mimic the symptoms of asthma and the differential diagnosis for asthma varies based on age.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] For older adults the differential diagnoses include medication-related cough, heart failure, lung embolism, interstitial lung disease, central airway obstruction, COPD, bronchitis, gastrointestinal reflux disease, recurrent respiratory infections, heart disease, and vocal cord dysfunction.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Many of the potential differential diagnoses for asthma commonly co-occur with asthma as well.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Other proposed preventative measures such as dietary changes, breastfeeding, supplements, and early exposure to pets or other common allergens do not currently have enough evidence to support their effectiveness.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The goal of asthma management is to reduce symptoms minimize the risk of complications such as exacerbations, reduced lung function, and medication side effects.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] This is done by evaluating asthma control and the risk of exacerbation, providing education and guidance on how to manage the disease, finding triggers and ways to minimize them, and medication.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma control should be reviewed during doctors appointments so that treatment can be adjusted accordingly.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] After a diagnosis of asthma is made the person receiving the diagnosis and their family should receive education about the disease and a plan for management.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Education includes information about avoiding triggers, self monitoring of symptoms or peak expiratory flow, an asthma action plan, asthma control and treatment options.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma action plans include management options to prevent and treat exacerbations as well as how to modify treatment based on symptoms or seek additional medical care.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] School based education programs on how to manage asthma decrease hospitalizations for asthma in school-aged children.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Non-medical strategies to manage asthma consist of avoiding exposure to triggers and management of factors that contribute to asthma severity or symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Exposure to cigarette smoke, from smoking or second-hand smoke, negatively affects asthma control and it is therefore recommended for those with asthma to refrain from smoking and limit exposure to second-hand smoke.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] For those with occupational asthma, it is recommended that sensitizers and allergens at work be avoided.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Due to the variety of potential allergens and the difficulty of eliminating exposure to allergens, current guidelines do not recommend that those with asthma avoid indoor or outdoor allergens.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Certain medications such as Aspirin, beta-blockers, and nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) can worsen asthma symptoms in some individuals.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] It is still considered safe for those with asthma to take these medications, unless they have caused adverse reactions in the past.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Guidelines encourage those with asthma to maintain a balanced and healthy diet due to benefits on overall wellbeing.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Regular physical activity is encouraged for those with asthma due to its positive effects on overall health, however, it does not result in any direct improvement in asthma symptoms and no specific form of exercise is more beneficial.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] For some, exercise may trigger asthma symptoms and therefore it is recommended that inhalers be used beforehand.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Pulmonary rehabilitation may be used to increase tolerance to exercise.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Obesity can cause asthma symptoms to be harder to control or cause more severe symptoms, weight loss in obese individuals is therefore recommended.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] There is not enough evidence that dietary changes, including restrictive diets or supplements are helpful in managing asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Alternative treatments such as acupuncture, air ionizers, manual therapies (osteopathic, chiropractic, physiotherapeutic and respiratory therapeutic manoeuvres), and breathing exercises are not recommended by clinical guidelines due to a lack of evidence that they are effective.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Breathing exercises do not decrease asthma exacerbations or improve lung functioning, however they can be used alongside medications to help control symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Medications for asthma are generally divided into three categories, controllers — taken daily to control symptoms, reduce exacerbations and decrease inflammation — relievers — taken as needed for severe symptoms or exacerbations — and additional medications added on to manage more severe asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Medications are prescribed at the lowest dose possible while still treating symptoms and preventing exacerbations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Devices for inhaled medications include pressurized metered dose inhaler (pMDI), dry-powder inhalers (DPI), mist inhalers and nebulizers.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The choice of delivery method depends on the type of medication used, local availability, age, and ability to use the inhaler properly.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] DPIs are difficult for children to use and are therefore discouraged in those under six years of age.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Spacers are used alongside pMDIs to increase the amount of medication inhaled.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The choice of medication used for asthma management depends on symptom control, risk factors, availability, adherence, ability to use the medication, cost and environmental impact.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] It typically takes one or two weeks for symptoms to improve after starting inhaled corticosteroids (ICS) and the response to medication is monitored whenever it is adjusted.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] If asthma symptoms and exacerbations remain well controlled after two or three months, the dosage of medication can be gradually reduced to achieve symptom control at the lowest possible dose of medication.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] If asthma symptoms and exacerbations persist despite two to three months of treatment with ICS factors such as inhaler technique, adherence, exposure to triggers, comorbidities, and alternative diagnoses are assessed before medication dosage is increased.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The first line treatment of asthma for children are ICS, for teenagers and adults guidelines recommend a combined ICS and long-acting beta2 agonist (LABA) inhaler.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] After a diagnosis of asthma is confirmed, ICS are started as soon as possible.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Guidelines also recommend that everyone diagnosed with asthma have access to a reliever inhaler in case of symptom flare ups.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In children younger than five, higher doses of ICS are used to treat persistent symptoms while older individuals may be treated with an additional medication.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Medical guidelines recommend referring people who have persistent symptoms despite adequate treatment to an asthma specialist (usually a respirologist or allergist).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Historically, asthma was treated with short-acting β2 agonists (SABA) as needed and ICS were only used if symptoms persisted.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Due to research suggesting that management with SABA over ICS was insufficient to prevent exacerbations, guidelines now prefer ICS over SABA.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] For those over the age of twelve, if asthma is not well controlled with an ICS/formoterol inhaler then guidelines recommend that medications be taken daily instead of on an as needed basis and gradually increased until symptoms are controlled.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] If higher doses of ICS/formoterol are not enough to control symptoms then there are several different medications that may be added in to help manage asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] These include the leukotriene receptor antagonists (LTRA) montelukast, a mist inhaler containing the LAMA tiotropium, and azithromycin.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In those with sensitization to aeroallergens, allergen-specific immunotherapy can increase tolerance to allergens by slowly introducing the allergen to an affected person.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] This is done through two different methods; subcutaneous immunotherapy — injections — and sublingual immunotherapy — under the tongue.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Biologics can be used to reduce inflammation that may play a role in asthma symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Finally, oral corticosteroids or bronchial thermoplasty may be used as last resorts for severe asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In children under the age of five who have comorbid atopic disorders and intermittent asthma symptoms or severe flare-ups a 8-12 week trial of low dose ICS as maintenance treatment and a SABA for flare-ups is recommended by NICE guidelines.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] If symptoms clear up during the trial then medication can be stopped and symptoms are monitored in the following months to watch for returning symptoms or exacerbation, in which case ICS and SABA can be started again.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Persistent symptoms are treated with increasing doses of ICS and an LTRA.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Low doses of ICS for maintenance and SABA as needed are used to manage asthma in children ages six to eleven, with ICS used whenever SABA are needed to treat flare-ups.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] If symptoms persist then the dose of ICS may be gradually increased, a LTRA can be added on top of inhalers or a low-dose ICS-LABA or ICS-formoterol can be used instead of ICS.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Treatment of asthma exacerbations involves several doses of bronchodilators, oral corticosteroids, and oxygen supplementation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Salbutamol (albuterol) is commonly used for treating exacerbations with several doses being administered every couple of hours until symptoms lessen.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] When exacerbations are severe or do not subside with inhaled medications, oral corticosteroids are used and continued for a week after the exacerbation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Oxygen therapy is also used to maintain a healthy oxygen saturation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Ipratropium, a short-acting anticholinergic, can also be used alongside other treatments to manage exacerbations in those experiencing moderate or severe symptoms.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Both intravenous magnesium sulfate and helium–oxygen therapy are not recommended by clinical guidelines for the management of exacerbations, however they may be used in those whose symptoms do not react to other first-line treatment options.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Staying with a treatment approach for preventing asthma exacerbations can be challenging, especially if the person is required to take medicine or treatments daily.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Reasons for low adherence range from a conscious decision to not follow the suggested medical treatment regime for various reasons including avoiding potential side effects, misinformation, or other beliefs about the medication.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Problems accessing the treatment and problems administering the treatment effectively can also result in lower adherence.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Various approaches have been undertaken to try and improve adherence to treatments to help people prevent serious asthma exacerbations, including digital interventions.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma symptoms usually manifest during early childhood.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Young children commonly experience asthma symptoms following viral infections, however only around half go on to develop asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Children who experience recurring asthma symptoms are more likely to develop airway inflammation and structural changes in the lungs.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] They may also have reduced lung function and are more likely to continue experiencing troublesome respiratory symptoms as they enter adulthood.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Despite asthma being more prevalent in children, mortality rates, morbidity, and usage of healthcare is higher amongst adults.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Over time, the mortality rate of asthma has gone down and it is now considered a rare cause of death.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Estimates from The Global Burden of Disease Study (GBD) collaboration state that over one thousand people die each day due to asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma mortality rates are typically higher in low-income regions due to lack of access to medical care.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The burden of disease is a measure of the overall impact of a disease on health.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] GBD estimates this impact using data on disease prevalence, deaths, and health surveys.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] It measures disease burden through years of life lost due to premature death (YLL) and years lived with disability (YLD).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] These two measures are combined to calculate disability-adjusted life years (DALYs), which represent the total health loss caused by a disease.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] YLD reflects both the severity of disability and how long it lasts.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In 2019, asthma was responsible for an estimated 21.6 million DALYs worldwide across all age groups.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] It was the 34th leading cause of disease burden globally and accounted for about one-fifth of all DALYs related to chronic respiratory diseases.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Nearly half of this burden was due to 10.2 million years lived with disability.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma was also the 24th leading cause of disability worldwide in 2019, with a slightly greater impact on males than females.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In 2023, approximately 363 million people worldwide were affected by asthma, and 442,000 people died from the disease.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Rates vary between countries, with prevalences between 1 and 29%.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] It is more common in developed than developing countries.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Within developed countries, it is more common in those who are economically disadvantaged, while in contrast, in developing countries, it is more common in the affluent.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The reasons for these differences are unclear.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Low- and middle-income countries make up more than 80% of the mortality.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] While asthma is more common in boys than girls, severe asthma occurs at almost equal rates.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In contrast adult women have a higher rate of asthma than men.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Overall, there is a slightly higher health burden on women than men.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma is more common in the young than in adults.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma was recognized in ancient egypt and was treated by drinking an incense mixture known as kyphi.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] It was officially named as a specific respiratory problem by Hippocrates c.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] 450 BC, with the Greek word for "panting" forming the basis of our modern name.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In 200 BC, it was believed to be at least partly related to the emotions.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In the 12th century, the Jewish physician and philosopher Maimonides wrote *Maqāla fī al-Rabw* ("Treatise on Asthma") in Arabic.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In the work, he described the symptoms of asthma, proposed dietary and therapeutic treatments, and emphasized the importance of clean air and climate in managing the condition.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Traditional Chinese medicine also offered medication for asthma, as indicated by a surviving 14th-century manuscript curated by the Wellcome Foundation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] A well-documented case in the 19th century was that of young Theodore Roosevelt (1858–1919).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] At that time there was no effective treatment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Roosevelt's youth was in large part shaped by his poor health, partly related to his asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] He experienced recurring nighttime asthma attacks that felt as if he was being smothered to death, terrifying the boy and his parents.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In 1873, one of the first papers in modern medicine on the subject tried to explain the pathophysiology of the disease while another in 1872, concluded that asthma can be cured by rubbing the chest with chloroform liniment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Medical treatment in 1880 included the use of intravenous doses of a drug called pilocarpine.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Bosworth theorized a connection between asthma and hay fever.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] At the beginning of the 20th century, treatment was focused on avoidance of allergens and the use of selective beta2-adrenergic agonists as treatment strategies.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Epinephrine (adrenaline) was first referred to as a treatment of asthma in 1905.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The asthma was relieved with this treatment by what was described as "vasomotor ataxia of the relaxing variety".
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The successful results of using epinephrine provided encouraging medical data on the hypothesis that asthma was due to vasodilation and the subsequent inflammation of the swelling of the bronchial mucosa.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In the 1930s, U.S. physician Alvan Barach created, by means of spirometry, the quantification of expiratory flow rates to nebulized epinephrine for those with asthma, which was the first published medical report on the effectiveness of bronchodilation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] During the 1930s to 1950s, asthma was known as one of the "holy seven" psychosomatic illnesses.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Its cause was considered to be psychological, with treatment often based on psychoanalysis and other talking cures.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] As these psychoanalysts interpreted the asthmatic wheeze as the suppressed cry of the child for its mother, they considered the treatment of depression to be especially important for individuals with asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In the 1940s, the first pure β-agonist to be synthesized was isoprenaline.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Both isoprenaline and adrenaline are catecholamines.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] However, isoprenaline was an effective bronchodilator that was more selective than epinephrine.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The efficacy of anecdotal applications of oral corticosteroids (OCS) for the asthma was published in 1952.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In 1958, the association between a treatment strategy of OCS and a reduction in eosinophils in the sputum was published.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The use of a pressurized metered dose inhaler was developed in the mid-1950s for the administration of adrenaline as well as isoproterenol, and was later used as a beta2-adrenergic agonist.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Inhaled corticosteroids and selective short-acting beta agonists came into wide use in the 1960s.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In 1967, adrenergic receptors were classified into the two subtypes of the β1 and the β2 adrenergic receptors.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The β2 adrenergic receptors were found to be dominant in the lungs as well as present in the alveolar airspace.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The discovery of the β2 adrenergic receptors allowed for the discovery and development of beta2 agonists.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Specifically, it allowed for the development of selective β2-agonists starting in the 1960s.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Between 1970 and 1985, the following countries saw a general rise in reported asthma mortality in people aged 5 to 34: Singapore, Australia, Japan, England/Wales, West Germany, Israel, United States, Netherlands, Canada, and France.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Additionally, New Zealand experienced a major epidemic of asthma in this period, which may have been due to inadequate maintenance therapy and long-term management of the disease amongst those affected, as well as delays in receiving care in emergencies.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] As of 2005, more "westernized," urbanized countries had much higher rates of asthma than "less developed" countries.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] However, exposure to urbanization alone has not been able to explain these disparities.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In the United States, the burden of asthma falls disproportionately on racial and ethnic minorities and economically underprivileged populations.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] As of 2016, the prevalence of asthma was highest in non-Hispanic black and Puerto Rican children.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] The prevalence of asthma was also over 1.5 times higher in Americans 100% below the poverty level than those 450% of the poverty level or higher.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] As of 2021, the mortality rate for black Americans with asthma was two times higher than for white Americans.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Neighborhoods in the United States with predominantly racial and ethnic minority populations are affected to a greater extent than predominantly white neighborhoods by air pollutants, which are a significant factor in the occurrence of asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Additionally, residents of areas that were more likely to be redlined have asthma emergency department visit rates 2.4 times higher than residents of areas that were less likely to be redlined.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] People with asthma often experience reduced quality of life, including fatigue, sleep problems, lower levels of physical activity, and difficulty concentrating.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] These problems can lead to missed days at school or work and can create financial and productivity challenges for families and communities.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Asthma also places a major economic burden on society.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In 2008, the estimated costs of asthma were between $49.36 million and $8,256 million in several high-income countries, including Canada, Germany, Singapore, Switzerland, and the United States.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] A later study found that the total annual cost of asthma in the United States had risen to $81.9 billion by 2013.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] There is less information available from low- and middle-income countries.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] However, the financial impact is greatest among people with severe or poorly controlled asthma.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] In developing countries, people with uncontrolled asthma account for about half of all asthma-related costs, despite making up only 10–20% of people with the disease.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/asthma] Worldwide, the financial burden of asthma is estimated to be greater than that of tuberculosis and HIV/AIDS combined.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] Bac*Dive* is a comprehensive resource containing diverse data on bacterial and archaeal strains, including taxonomy, morphology, physiology, sampling and environmental data and sequence information.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] The database is built on a base of curated data from culture collections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] In 2025 Bac*Dive* contains information on 99,392 strains, including 21,168 type strains.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] The database is hosted by the Leibniz Institute DSMZ - German Collection of Microorganisms and Cell Cultures GmbH and is part of the integrated DSMZ Digital Diversity infrastructure.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] Bac*Dive* is a member of de.NBI - the German Network for Bioinformatics Infrastructure, as well as ELIXIR.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] The Global Biodata Coalition designated Bac*Dive* a Global Core Biodata Resource (GCBR) in 2022.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] In 2023, Bac*Dive* was additionally named as an ELIXIR Core Data Resource.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] Bac*Dive* was initially released in April 2012 to standardize and make publicly available strain data of culture collections, other compendia, and publications.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] The first release, contained 89,758 entries for 18,157 strains and 179 different used data fields.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] Today (as of December 2024), the database encompassed over 1000 different data fields.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] The database now comprises 2,709,516 entries for 99,392 strains.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] Data for each strain is divided into the categories "Name and taxonomic classification", "Morphology", "Culture and growth conditions, "Physiology and metabolism", "Isolation, sampling and environmental information." "Safety information", "Sequence information".
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] Since 2023 high-quality predicted data produced using machine learning models trained on curated *BacDive* data can be found in an additional section titled "Genome-based predictions".
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] Data can be accessed either via a GUI, via the RESTful web service., or via a SPARQL endpoint.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] The GUI offers a simple search featuring auto-completion for searching strains by name, culture collection number, NCBI Tax ID or INSDC sequence accession number.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] Additionally, the user can use the advanced search, which enables the search in 130 data fields and gives the opportunity of complex queries by combining several fields.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] Data can be downloaded in CSV format for one or multiple strains.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] Via the RESTful web service portal Bac*Dive* content can be accessed automatically (a free registration is needed).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] To support the use of the API, software clients in Python and R are available.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacdive] For data that are outside the focus of Bac*Dive*, links to other databases are provided.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Generally, the basic morphologies are spheres (coccus) and round-ended cylinders or rod shaped (bacillus).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] But, there are also other morphologies such as helically twisted cylinders (example *Spirochetes*), cylinders curved in one plane (selenomonads) and unusual morphologies (the square, flat box-shaped cells of the Archaean genus *Haloquadratum)*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Other arrangements include pairs, tetrads, clusters, chains and palisades.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] A **coccus** (plural *cocci*, from the Latin *coccinus* (scarlet) and derived from the Greek *kokkos* (berry)), is any microorganism (usually bacteria) whose overall shape is spherical or nearly spherical.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Coccus refers to the shape of the bacteria and can contain multiple genera, such as staphylococci or streptococci.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Cocci can grow in pairs, chains, or clusters, depending on their orientation and attachment during cell division.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] In contrast to many bacilli-shaped bacteria, most cocci bacteria do not have flagella and are non-motile.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Cocci is an English loanword of a modern or Neo-Latin noun, which in turn stems from the Greek masculine noun κόκκος (*cóccos*) meaning 'berry'.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Important human diseases caused by coccoid bacteria include staphylococcal infections, some types of food poisoning, some urinary tract infections, toxic shock syndrome, gonorrhea, as well as some forms of meningitis, throat infections, pneumonias, and sinusitis.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] The gram-positive cocci are a large group of bacteria with similar morphology.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] All are spherical or nearly so, but they vary considerably in size.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Members of some genera are identifiable by the way cells are attached to one another: in pockets, in chains, or grape-like clusters.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] These arrangements reflect patterns of cell division and that cells stick together.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] *Sarcina* cells, for example, are arranged in cubical pockets because cell division alternates regularly among the three perpendicular planes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] *Streptococcus* spp. resemble a string of beads because division always occurs in the same plane.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Some of these strings, for example, *S. pneumoniae**,* are only two cells long.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] They are called *diplococci.* Species of *Staphylococcus* have no regular plane of division.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] The various gram-positive cocci differ physiologically and by habitat.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] *Micrococcus* spp. are obligate aerobes that inhabit human skin.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] *Staphylococcus* spp. also inhabit human skin, but they are facultative anaerobes.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] They ferment sugars, producing lactic acid as an end product.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Many of these species produce carotenoid pigments, which color their colonies yellow or orange.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] *Staphylococcus aureus* is a major human pathogen.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] It can infect almost any tissue in the body, frequently the skin.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] It often causes nosocomial (hospital-acquired) infections.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] The genus *Moraxella* belongs to the family *Moraxellaceae*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] However, only one has a morphology of diplococcus, *M. catarrhalis*, a salient pathogen contributing to infections in the human body.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] The species *Streptococcus pneumoniae* belongs to the genus *Streptococcus* and the family *Streptococcaceae*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] The genus *Streptococcus* has around 129 species and 23 subspecies that benefit many microbiomes on the human body.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] There are many species that show non-pathogenic characteristics; however, there are some, like *S. pneumoniae*, that exhibit pathogenic characteristics in the human body.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] The genus *Enterococcus* belongs to the family *Enterococcaceae*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] This genus is divided into 58 species and two subspecies.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] These gram-positive, coccoid bacteria were once thought to be harmless to the human body.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] However, within the last ten years, there has been an influx of nosocomial pathogens originating from *Enterococcus* bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] A **bacillus** (pl.: **bacilli**), also called a **bacilliform bacterium** or often just a **rod** (when the context makes the sense clear), is a rod-shaped bacterium or archaeon.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Bacilli are found in many different taxonomic groups of bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] However, the name *Bacillus*, capitalized and italicized, refers to a specific genus of bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] The name Bacilli, capitalized but not italicized, can also refer to a less specific taxonomic group of bacteria that includes two orders, one of which contains the genus *Bacillus*.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] When the word is formatted with lowercase and not italicized, 'bacillus', it will most likely be referring to shape and not to the genus.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Bacilliform bacteria are also often simply called rods when the bacteriologic context is clear.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Bacilli usually divide in the same plane and are solitary, but can combine to form diplobacilli, streptobacilli, and palisades.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] There is no connection between the shape of a bacterium and its color upon Gram staining; there are both gram-positive rods and gram-negative rods.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] MacConkey agar can be used to distinguish among gram-negative bacilli such as *E. coli* and salmonella.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] A **coccobacillus** (plural **coccobacilli**), or **bacillococcus**, is a type of bacterium with a shape intermediate between cocci (spherical bacteria) and bacilli (rod-shaped bacteria).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Coccobacilli, then, are very short rods which may be mistaken for cocci.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] The word *coccobacillus* reflects an intermediate shape between *coccus* (spherical) and *bacillus* (elongated).
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Bacteria are known to evolve specific traits to survive in their ideal environment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Bacteria-caused illnesses hinge on the bacteria's physiology and their ability to interact with their environment, including the ability to shapeshift.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Researchers discovered a protein that allows the bacterium *Vibrio cholerae* to morph into a corkscrew shape that likely helps it twist into — and then escape — the protective mucus that lines the inside of the gut.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] A spirillum (plural spirilla) is a rigid spiral bacterium that is gram-negative and frequently has external amphitrichous or lophotrichous flagella.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] A spirochete (plural spirochetes) is a very thin, elongate, flexible, spiral bacteria that is motile via internal periplasmic flagella inside the outer membrane.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacillus-shape] Owing to their morphological properties, spirochetes are difficult to Gram-stain but may be visualized using dark field microscopy or Warthin–Starry stain.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] Cells of *B. fragilis* are rod-shaped to pleomorphic with a cell size range of 0.5–1.5 × 1.0–6.0 μm.*B. fragilis* is a Gram-negative bacterium and does not possess flagella or cilia, making it immotile.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] However, it does utilize peritrichous fimbriae for adhesion to other molecular structures.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] *B. fragilis* also utilizes a complex series of surface proteins, lipopolysaccharide chains, and outer membrane vesicles to help survive the volatile intestinal micro-environment.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] The complex environmental-sensory system allows *B. fragilis* to survive and adapt in the ever-changing human gut microbiome.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] This system is composed of many components and can effectively handle a variety of threats to the bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] Proteins such as catalase, superoxide dismutase, and alkyl hydroperoxide reductase protect the organism from harmful oxygen radicals.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] This permits growth in the presence of nanomolar concentrations of O2.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] Member of the genus *Bacteroides* are characterized with having the highest numbers of antibiotic resistance mechanisms accompanied by the highest resistance rates amongst anaerobic bacteria.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] The high resistance to antibiotics of *B.fragilis* is mainly attributed to genetic plasticity.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] Species of the Bacteroidaceae have displayed increasing resistance to antimicrobial agents such as cefoxitin, clindamycin, metronidazole, carbapenems, and fluoroquinolones.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] The *B. fragilis* group is the most commonly isolated Bacteroidaceae in anaerobic infections, especially those that originate from the gastrointestinal microbiota.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] *B. fragilis* is the most prevalent organism in the *B. fragilis* group, accounting for 41% to 78% of the isolates of the group.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] These organisms are resistant to penicillin by virtue of production of beta-lactamase, and by other unknown factors.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] This group was formerly classified as subspecies of *B. fragilis* (i.e.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] They have been reclassified into distinct species on the basis of DNA homology studies.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] *B. fragilis* (formerly known as *B. f.* ssp.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] *fragilis*) is often recovered from blood, pleural fluid, peritoneal fluid, wounds, and brain abscesses.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] Although the *B. fragilis* group is the most common species found in clinical specimens, it is the least common *Bacteroides* present in fecal microbiota, comprising only 0.5% of the bacteria present in stool.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] Their pathogenicity partly results from their ability to produce capsular polysaccharide, which is protective against phagocytosis and stimulates abscess formation.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] Enterotoxigenic *B. fragilis* is a significant source of chronic inflammation in the context of gastrointestinal disease and has been implicated as a risk factor for colorectal cancer.
[src:bacteroides-fragilis/bacteroides-fragilis] The inflammation caused by *B. fragilis* induces spermine oxidase, a polyamine catabolic enzyme, that may result in production of increased reactive oxygen species and DNA damage leading to colon tumorigenesis.
